<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economists Predict 3 percent Growth in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The nation's leading business
economists predicted that the U.S. economy will slow in time to
avert an increase in inflation, the Wall Street Journal reported
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 34-member forecasting panel of the National Association of
Business Economists (NABE) said the U.S. economy will expand 3
percent in 1999, faster than 2.1 percent the forecasters predicted
in November, though slower than the 3.9 percent growth rate in
1998. For 2000, the forecasters see growth of 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NABE survey also noted that 23 percent of those surveyed
feel that current monetary policy is "too stimulative" for the
economy, while 75 percent think it is "about right". The slight
shift in pessimism didn't change the opinion of the majority of
panelists who neither expect nor prefer any change in short-term
interest rates in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Slightly more than half of the NABE panelists believe the stock
market will rally further this year. In fact, only 11 percent
think the market will slide for the rest of 1999, which signals a
shift from the more pessimistic view evidenced in the NABE's
earlier survey.
</P>
<P>
NABE economists also expect unemployment to remain low,
averaging 4.5 percent in 1999, as was seen last year, and rising
to 4.7 in 2000. Inflation, as measured by the consumer price
index, is also expected to remain tame. Economists project an
increase to 2 percent in 1999 and 2.3 percent in 2000, compared
with the 1.6 percent rate in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Almost 80 percent of the NABE forecasting panel also feels that
the current economic expansion, which has already lasted 96
months, will become the longest upswing in U.S. history. The
record for economic expansion took place between 1961 and 1969,
and lasted 106 months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
