<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Welcomes Libya's Flexibility over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid Wednesday expressed welcome to Libya's flexible
stance on resolving the Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters about the issue, Abdel-Meguid voiced hope
that Libya's flexibility would lead to positive reaction from the
United States and Britain, which are involved in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi said Tuesday that he is willing
to accept guarantees and assurances by Saudi Arabia and South
Africa over resolving the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi said South African President Nelson Mandela's words are
sufficient and "stronger than a resolution adopted by the United
Nations Security Council" on resolving the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been disputing with the U.S. and Britain over the
trial of two Libyans suspected of blowing up a Pan Am jetliner in
1988 over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid stressed that Libya has the right to get
guarantees for a fair trial of the two Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
Libya was seeking guarantees for the two suspects' security and
fair trial after agreeing to let them stand trial in the
Netherlands by Scottish judges under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief said that he will discuss with Gaddafi
the Lockerbie issue during the Libyan leader's planned visit to
Egypt in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said that Gaddafi's upcoming visit will afford "a
good opportunity" for more cooperation between Libya and Egypt,
and Libya and the pan-Arab forum in resolving Tripoli's disputes
with the two Western powers.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Wednesday that
Gaddafi is due to arrive in Cairo on Friday for a two-day visit,
during which he will confer with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on the prospects of handing over the two Libyans for trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
