<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Rally to Beat Jilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A scoring drought in the dying
minutes proved to be costly as Jilin Northeast Tigers squandered
the hard-fought lead and finally were squeaked by Liaoning Hunters
in the 17th round of China Basketball League on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hunters, the runners-up last season, sparked a 11-0 outburst in
the last five minutes to edged the Tigers for their 13th win after
17 games.
</P>
<P>
Trailing 50-49 at halftime, Tigers managed to take the lead at
74-70 after the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Under the inspiration by the home fans, Jilin, who relegated
from the second division, kept the lead until Liaoning used a 11-0
run to seal the game.
</P>
<P>
"My players did try their best though they were beaten," said
Li Xiaojun, head coach of Tigers. "It was very normal thing that
Liaoning won over us becasue they were a strong and better team."
</P>
<P>
Hunters standed second on the league standings, three games shy
of Bayi Rockets, who recorded 16-1.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Sharks, which bowed to Zhejiang Cyclone in a 108-113
loss Wednesday, shared third with Hongyuan Guangdong Tigers, who
beat Jinan Army Pengusus 102-82.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Aoshen, who snapped a winning streak by reigning
champions Rockets in the 15th round, defeated Beijing Ducks 104-96
for their fourth win in a row.
</P>
<P>
Ducks wasted a chance to force an ovetime when they cut the
deficit to 96-98 with one minute left but a three-pointer in the
last second by Aoshen killed the hope of Ducks.
</P>
<P>
Bayi kept their authority in a one-sided matchup by routing
languishing Jiangsu Dragons 138-92.
</P>
<P>
In Chengdu, Sichuang Panda upset the visiting Shandong Flaming
Bulls 91-83 for their seventh victory of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
