<HEADLINE> 1999 China Business Summit to Focus on Long-term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The 1999 China Business Summit, to
be held in late April, will focus its attention on issues like how
China can maintain the speed of its reforms and ensure the success
of long-term restructuring while cushioning the impact of economic
cycles, officials of the World Economic Forum (WEF) told Xinhua
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Other major topics to be discussed during the summit include
the challenges of financial security in the context of prolonged
recession in Asia, how the Chinese government plans to increase
the inflow of the foreign direct investment (FDI), and China's
employment and labor markets reforms.
</P>
<P>
The China Business Summit, sponsored by the Geneva-based WEF
since 1981, has attracted thousands of government officials,
intellectuals, businessmen and reporters from all over the world
to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Different from the previous summits, the venue of the 1999
summit will be extended from Beijing on April 25-27 to Shanghai on
April 27-28.
</P>
<P>
The WEF officials expected the 1999 summit to provide a
privileged framework to discuss the part private and public
sectors can play to boost domestic investment demand and consumer
demand and to present the most recent update on the economic
conditions and options open to the nation's decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
They also hoped that the summit will provide foreign
participants with an opportunity to expand their network and meet
the new generation of Chinese business leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demirel: Economic Cooperation to be Key of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
said here Wednesday that the economic cooperation will be the key
of peace in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Demirel made the remarks at the Ankara Esenboga Airport when
he returned from the second Developing Eight (D-8) summit held
in Dhaka, capital of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that the basic targets of the D-8 summit which
can be defined as improvement of the economic cooperation and as
increasing the trade between the D-8 member countries were
confirmed once more in the Dhaka Declaration adopted in this
summit.
</P>
<P>
He added that the D-8 summit is a useful initiative which
helps Turkey to benefit from the opportunities of the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
Demirel believed that the economic cooperation movement will be
a significant investment for the future.
</P>
<P>
However, the 33-point declaration expressed concern over the
lack of progress in reforming and strengthening the international
financial system to protect the interest of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The D-8, an economic group comprising Bangladesh, Pakistan,
Iran, Nigeria, Egypt, Turkey, Indonesia and Malaysia, was launched
in Istanbul, the largest city in Turkey, in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
