<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Backs Calls for IRA Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
in an interview published on Wednesday, supported calls for the
Irish Republican Army or IRA to hand over arms before its
political wing, Sinn Fein, enters Northern Ireland government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to The Scotsman newspaper, the prime minister
dismissed claims by a Sinn Fein leader that the IRA could not hand
over its weapons.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein says an IRA weapons handover is not required by the
April 1998 agreement as a precondition for their entry into
government.
</P>
<P>
"They can do it, if they wish to do it," Blair said, adding the
Irish republicans should "listen to the people." The pro-British
politicians in Northern Ireland have repeatedly called for the IRA
disarmament to guarantee a permanent peace in the province.
</P>
<P>
"We must also make sure that the whole of the agreement is
implemented, and that includes the decommissioning (surrender of
weapons) part of it," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The reason for that is perfectly simple: people have got to
know if they are sitting down with people who have given up
violence for good," Blair added.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for creation of an coalition provincial government
in Belfast falls on March 10 with fears that a peace agreement
signed in the British-ruled province last April could founder if
it is not met because of the arms deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The agreement brought a tentative halt to three decades of
conflict between Protestant unionists who want Northern Ireland to
remain British and Roman Catholic republicans who seek unification
with the Irish Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
