<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Blames Syria for Supporting Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Moshe
Arens said on Wednesday that the situation in Lebanon will remain
unstable if Syria continues to support the Shiite Muslim
guerrilla group Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Arens said that "we
basically do not have a stable situation in Lebanon as long as
the Syrians continue to consent to activities of the Hezbollah
guerrillas."
</P>
<P>
Arens noted that it is Syria's strategy to make a linkage
between the demand for an Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon
and the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in the
1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
He said that by encouraging the Hezbollah guerrillas to attack
Israeli targets in south Lebanon, Syria wants to pressure Israel
to withdraw from both Lebanon and the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The tensions in south Lebanon have been escalated as seven
Israelis including a general were killed by the Hezbollah
guerrillas in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with a
claimed aim of protecting its northern areas from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas. Since then, Lebanon's resistance
movement spearheaded by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party
of God, has been fighting to drive Israeli troops out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government insisted that only after the Lebanese
government agreed to disarm Hezbollah and deploy its troops in
south Lebanon to prevent cross-border attacks, Israel would
pull its troops out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But both Lebanon and Syria have rejected the Israeli proposal,
noting that Israel must withdraw unconditionally. Syria
maintains about 30,000 troops in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
