<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharon's Proposal for National Unity Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli political figures across
party lines on Wednesday rejected Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon's
proposal for postponing the national elections and forming an
emergency national unity government.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman said it is too late to create such a
unity government because the election campaign is under way,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who the radio said had
earlier supported the idea, also rejected it.
</P>
<P>
The major opposition parties including Labor, the Center Party
and Meretz, also turned down the initiative.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's suggestion was termed by the Labor Party as another
proof that the Netanyahu government has failed to solve any
pressing problems.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move, Sharon told Israel Radio Tuesday night that
he had proposed to create a national unity government by Labor and
the Likud in order to resolve the issues of Lebanon and peace
talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"We need to set up an emergency government immediately... in
order to reach a decision on unilateral withdrawal from Lebanon
and on implementing the agreement with the Palestinians," Sharon
said.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that Sharon floated the idea in response
to Labor Party leader Barak's pledge made Tuesday that he would
withdraw Israeli troops from south Lebanon within a year if he
wins the prime ministership in the May elections.
</P>
<P>
Observers said Netanyahu rejected the idea only after it had
been denied by the Labor so as to put the blame of failing to form
a unity government on the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
The mounting Israeli casualties in south Lebanon have led to
growing public pressure in Israel for a unilateral troop
withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
