<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Again Meets Air Defense Commanders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on
Wednesday met with military commanders to discuss air defense
issues, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In his capacity as commander-in-chief of the Iraqi armed
forces, Saddam met with commander of air defense forces, head of
the military industry and other senior air defense officers, said
INA. But it did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
This was the second day in a run that Saddam met with his air
defense lieutenants. Reports said he talked with them Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Saddam also received his ministers of oil and military
industry, air defense commander and some specialists in the air
defense field on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
These meetings came after the U.S. and Britain had intensified
their air raids on "civilian and military targets" in the no-fly
zones in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday and Monday, U.S. and British warplanes bombed the
control and communications systems of the important sixth relay
station on the Iraqi-Turkish pipeline and Ein Zala oil field,
killing two civilians and wounding 11 others.
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-December U.S.-British air strikes on Iraq, Saddam
has met a number of times with senior officials, military
commanders and specialists of air defense to counter allied air
superority.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between Iraqi air defense units and U.S. and British
jets patrolling the no-fly zones have almost become daily
occurrence since the mid-December bombardment.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad suppression." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Urges Compliance Prior to March 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The NATO chief urged on Wednesday
the conflicting parties in Kosovo to comply with the cease-fire
and to try to make the most of the remaining time for reaching a
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana told the press that
compliance was a very important word between now and March 15, the
date set for the restart of the peace talks between the Yugoslav
authorities and the ethnic Albanians from the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The period between now and March 15 is the time for
cooperation," said Solana, "and the time for finding a final
solution to the Kosovo crisis."
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief made the remark after being briefed by United
States Kosovo envoy Christopher Hill and European Union Kosovo
envoy Wolfgang Petritsch about the development of the peace
process after the Rambouillet negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Solana described the resignation of hardline ethnic Albanian
leader Adem Demaci on Tuesday as "a very important decision taken
by the ethnic Albanian side". The move was seen as to have
increased the possibility for the ethnic Albanians to sign up the
peace deal provisionally agreed at Rambouillet outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
Now it was up to the Serbian side to do the same to reach the
peace deal, added the NATO chief.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy Hill said after briefing the NATO
decision-makers that the Kosovo Liberation Army is ready to sign
the peace deal which it demanded at Rambouillet on February 24
extra time to consult within its own ranks.
</P>
<P>
Hill urged both sides not to abuse the situation in Kosovo nor
the time running up to March 15 after admitting that there had
been non-compliance and "ugly incidents" of late.
</P>
<P>
Both envoys stressed that the implementation of the peace deal
by international ground troops will benefit both the ethnic
Albanians and the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no political agreement without the
implementation," said Hill who is to return to Pristina, Kosovo,
to continue diplomatic efforts while Petritsch described the peace
implementation as "part and parcel" of the deal to be signed by
all sides.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks are scheduled to resume on March 15 in a French
air base to focus on the implementation clause of the peace deal
proposed by the six-nation Contact Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
