<HEADLINE> Jordan Cuts Economic Dependence on Iraq: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has reduced its
economic dependence on Iraq by 50 percent in a bid to expand its
ties with the Gulf Arab countries, visiting Jordanian Foreign
Minister Abdul Ilah al-Khatib said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with local media before concluding his
two-day visit to Kuwait, al-Khatib said Jordan was going through
"a very difficult stage and is trying to benefit as much as
possible from the Gulf states."
</P>
<P>
"The volume of trade has been reduced from 400 million
U.S. dollars to 200 million dollars," al-Khatib was quoted as
saying by Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Jordan relys heavily on trade with Iraq and Iraq's oil which
Amman imports at preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
On his meeting last week with Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad
al-Sahhaf, al-Khatib said he had told his Iraqi counterpart that
Baghdad should prove its good will toward Arab states by releasing
Kuwaitis still detained in Iraqi jails.
</P>
<P>
"He (al-Sahhaf) said that there are no Kuwaiti prisoners of
war in Iraq," the Jordanian official said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib stressed that the Iraqi regime should "respect the
characteristics of the regional states and the aspiration of Arab
people."
</P>
<P>
He also urged Iraq to respect the leadership of neighboring
Arab states and refrain from attempting to destabilize the region.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-December U.S.-British air raids on Iraq, the Iraqi
leadership had appealed to Kuwaitis and Saudis to revolt against
their rulers, who allowed U.S. and British troops to use their
territories for attacks on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
