<HEADLINE> Telecom Revolution in Africa Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- ICO Global Communications, the
world-wide mobile telephone company, has predicted a major
telecommunication revolution in Africa in 1999 which will touch
not only urban centers but remote rural areas as well.
</P>
<P>
The African connection agenda drawn up by the ministers at
Africa Telecom '98 has clearly paved the way for a renaissance in
the telecommunications sector in Africa, Khaya Dlukulu, who is
regional general manager for ICO in Africa, said in a despatch
sent to Zambian News Agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the African telecom summit now underway in Ghana,
Dlukulu predicted that 1999 will mark the year that will see the
beginning of the GMPCS (Global Mobile Personal Communications
Services) via satellite.
</P>
<P>
Cellular and global telephony system will have a significant
impact on Africa. "We are looking forward to operating in an
environment in which there is fair and vigorous competition among
all players," he said.
</P>
<P>
ICO Global Communications has already won support from ten
African countries that have invested over 50 million U.S. Dollars
in the new system.
</P>
<P>
The company was established in January 1995 as a private
company to provide global mobile personal communications by
satellite, including digital voice, data, fax and messaging
services.
</P>
<P>
It has so far raised more than three billion Dollars in equity
contributions and has 60 investors comprising telecommunications
and technology companies from 50 markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
According to figures provided by the International
Telecommunications Union (ITU), the density of telephones in
Africa will only be two per 100 people in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
This compares markedly with 35 per 100 in the Americas and more
than 40 in Europe.
</P>
<P>
ITU also calculates that the average distance between phones in
Africa is currently at about 50 kilometers and in some cases
country-dwellers may have to walk for several days to the nearest
telephone.
</P>
<P>
When fully operational, ICO's service will be based on a new
generation of pocket-sized mobile phones which will allow users
in Africa to make and receive calls at any time, and from any
where on the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
