<HEADLINE> Ramadhan: Iraq Ready for Talks with Arab Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadhan on Wednesday said Iraq is ready for dialog with Arab
countries to find solutions that will rebuild Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Ramadhan made the remarks in a speech delivered at the
National Defense College, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said the U.S. and Britain always appeared to
advocate democracy, but in fact they themselves trampled on
democracy when interfering in the internal affairs of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He added that this phenomenon did not exist 15 years ago, but
it exists now because of the weakness of some Arab governments in
confronting the American tyranny.
</P>
<P>
Ramadhan said that the mid-December U.S.-British air strikes
against Iraq would not have been stopped if it had not been for
the Arab masses' anger against this aggression.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations that took place in Arab capitals at that
time proved that the U.S. and British schemes against Iraq
failed, he added.
</P>
<P>
In mid-December, the U.S. and British launched air strikes on
Iraq to retaliate what they claimed the Iraqi failure to fully
cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors in charge of eliminating
Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Ramadhan slammed the imposition of the no-fly
zones on Iraq, saying it is an illegal U.S.-British unilateral
action which is not based on the international legitimacy and has
no authorization from the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"The no-fly zones aim at interfering in Iraq's internal
affairs and national sovereignty," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies imposed the no-fly zones in the wake of
the 1991 Gulf War, with the claimed aim of protecting the Kurds in
the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's
suppression."
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-December bombardment, clashes between U.S. and
British jets patrolling the restricted zones and the Iraqi air
defense forces have almost become daily occurrence. 
</P>
