<HEADLINE> British FM in Russia to Probe Nuke Waste Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook arrived in northern Russia Wednesday on a three-day visit
intended to help Moscow utilize its nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
He landed in the town of Murmansk on the northwestern Kola
Peninsula, home to the Northern Fleet and one of the largest and
potentially most dangerous concentrations of nuclear waste in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Murmansk is mired in a growing financial and ecological crisis
as more and more nuclear-powered submarines are taken out of
service.
</P>
<P>
Russia's nuclear processing industry is facing grave
difficulties as much of the waste is either badly stored in
disintegrating containers or simply abandoned.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Murmansk, Cook will visit an Atomflot plant,
which processes liquid nuclear waste, and Lepse, Russia's only and
Europe's largest barge used for storing radioactive waste, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Cook was scheduled to fly from Murmansk to Moscow on the
evening later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He will hold talks with his Russian counterpart, Igor Ivanov,
and meet with Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cook will also meet with British businessmen working in Russia.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, he and Ivanov will fly to the Black Sea resort city
of Sochi for a meeting with Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov, who is currently vacationing there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
