<HEADLINE> WB Finances Uganda's Rice Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) arm of the World Bank, will lend 2.4 million
U.S. dollars to help finance Uganda's rice growing and processing
facility.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Wednesday afternoon by the World Bank
(Uganda) said that the project, Tilda Uganda Ltd (TUL) ,
privatizes and rehabilitates the bankrupt kibimba rice scheme
which was established in eastern Uganda in 1973 by the
governments of Uganda and China as a joint venture.
</P>
<P>
The TUL , a privately owned company established for the
implementation of the project, acquired the rice operation in
1997 through Uganda's privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The company plans to produce 3,000 tons of milled rice, 2,400
tons of maize and 200 tons of soya each year. The rice mill will
have a capacity of five tons per hour, processing rice grown by
small holders in the area as well as the farm's crops.
</P>
<P>
IFC's Director for Sub-Sahara Africa Cesare Calari said the
project will produce high quality rice for the first time in
Uganda and reduce imports. thereby saving foreign exchange for the
country.
</P>
<P>
It will also increase employment where it is much needed in
rural eastern Uganda, the press release added.
</P>
<P>
IFC fosters economic growth in the developing world by
financing private sector investments, mobilizing capital in the
international financial markets, and providing technical
assistance and advice to governments and businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
