<HEADLINE> Mandela Meets Burundian Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Wednesday met Burundian President Pierre Buyoya's
special envoy and discussed with him the peace process in the
country, Mandela's office said.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Burundian Justice Minister Terence
Sinunguruza, Mandela said he supported the peace efforts of
Burundians and that there was always a peace resolution to any
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The president is of the view that no conflict is above
peaceful resolution through negotiations, and that a resolution of
this particular conflict would send a powerful message to the
troubled Great Lakes region, and indeed other parts of the world,
that divisions which many view as intractable are indeed capable
of resolution."
</P>
<P>
"A sustainable settlement in Burundi can give a lead to the
other states in the region," the office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Mandela emphasized the need to promote peaceful processes in
Africa as a whole. "Conflict in any one part of Africa affects
Africans everywhere," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the image of Africa as "a continent imprisoned by
conflict and famine" had kept away foreign investors and tourists.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the peace process in Burundi had been
nurtured and supported by African initiatives, and reflected the
commitment of African states to assume responsibility for
fostering peace, prosperity and democracy in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The statement said South Africa supported the peace process in
Burundi facilitated by former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's legal adviser, Fink Haysom, currently presides over
the committee of Burundians seeking agreement on constitutional
arrangements for Burundi.
</P>
<P>
General Andrew Masondo of the South African National Defense
Force is assisting the committee in dealing with a cease-fire and
related military matters.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa will continue to support this important process."
</P>
<P>
Burundi has been plagued by constant coups d'etat and civil
wars. 
</P>
