<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protein in Brain Could Help Cure Baldness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- German scientists have suggested
that substances which make brain cells grow might lead to
treatments for baldness, New Scientist magazine reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ralf Paus and his colleagues at Humboldt University in Berlin,
Germany, who made the discovery, said it may also help people get
rid of unwanted body hair.
</P>
<P>
Experiments with shaved mice showed that just before
shrivelling phase, hair follicles of the mice are awash with two
growth factors, and the two genes producing them are abnormally
active, which suggested the chemicals actually trigger the
shrinking of follicles.
</P>
<P>
To confirm this, the researchers engineered mice to churn out
too much of one of the growth factors. As expected, their hair
fell out earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
Conversely, hair took longer than normal to fall out in
"knockout" mice that could not make either protein.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first evidence that growth factors previously
thought to be important for the development of brain cells are
also important for the growth of hair follicles," said the
researchers.
</P>
<P>
They also found that the two substances work by binding to a
receptor on a cell, which suggested that drugs blocking the
receptor could prevent hair loss, while others that mimic the
brain proteins and bind to the receptor might help shed unwanted
hair.
</P>
<P>
However, the scientists pointed out that it is too early to say
whether the mouse results are relevant to humans, as their hair
growth is much more erratic than in mice.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hani's Killer to Marry in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Janusz Walus, a killer of
former South African Communist Party leader Chris Hani, will marry
his girl friend next Wednesday in jail.
</P>
<P>
Walus, 47, will marry Berril Roy, his girl friend, at Pretoria
maximum security prison, where he is serving a life term for the
murder of Hani, South African Press Association reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The South African Correctional Services Department confirmed
Wednesday it had granted permission for the couple to marry in a
prison office under strict conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, the couple would not be allowed to consummate their
marriage, as "there were no conjugal rights in South African
prisons", a correctional services spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Walus and his collaborator, South African Clive Derby-Lewis,
have applied for amnesty for killing Hani in 1993. The Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) had not yet delivered its verdict
on the amnesty application.
</P>
<P>
In terms of prison regulations, the only guests allowed during
the wedding ceremony were the bride and groom's parents or
guardians and the children of either of them. The bride and the
guests would have to leave after the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Roy, 32, was a qualified church minister and gospel singer and
had campaigned for several years for the release of political
prisoners, a close friend of Walus said.
</P>
<P>
She is divorced and has two children from her first marriage.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, the Pretoria High Court granted Walus a
divorce from his Polish wife Wanda. The couple were married in
1976 but she and their daughter stayed behind in Poland when Walus
left that country for political reasons in 1981.  
</P>
</TEXT>
