<HEADLINE> S. African Police to Work Better: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Within three years South
Africans would have the best equipped and trained police service
possible under the circumstances, South African Police Services
Chief Executive Officer Meyer Kahn said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a security protection exhibition near Johannesburg,
Kahn said the police was redirecting 400 million Rand (67 million
U.S. Dollars) annually from non-productive activities to improve
equipment and resources.
</P>
<P>
The efficiency of the police force was growing as the battle
against the malaise in the police was being won, South African
Press Association quoted Kahn as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 200 local and international companies are showcasing
their latest hi-tech security systems and products at the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Kahn said there was a 21 percent drop in police absentee levels
and 27 percent drop in incidence of the "blue flu" - police
officers reporting sick on Mondays, Fridays and public holidays.
</P>
<P>
He said most kinds of crimes in South Africa were stabilizing
or decreasing. But he admitted street crimes such as robbery,
residential break-ins and car hijackings have shown an increase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa's opposition parties Wednesday launched
a new round of attacks on the government for its failure to curb
crime.
</P>
<P>
In parliament, the National Party (NP) and the African
Christian Democratic Party (ACDP) slammed the government for its
"appalling" performance on crime. They said crime levels had gone
up since the African National Congress (ANC) came to power in
1994.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reasonable place in this country where crime is
not taking place: Parliament, the president's residence, churches,
schools and the national intelligence premises have become
targets," ACDP leader Kenneth Meshoe said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that South Africa has one of the worst rates of
murder and rape in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
