<HEADLINE> Russian Lawmaker: Corruption Erodes Executive Branch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian lawmaker said
Wednesday that corruption "has reached an unprecedented scale,
with the executive branch and law enforcement agencies infested to
a large extent."
</P>
<P>
Alexander Kulikov, chairman of the Anti-Corruption Commission
of the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, told a press
conference that the Prosecutor General's Office, the Interior
Ministry, the Federal Security Service and regional law
enforcement had opened 45 criminal cases to follow up on his
commission's findings.
</P>
<P>
He said 51 reviews are underway concerning complicity in
corruption of various senior officials, in particular former prime
ministers Viktor Chernomyrdin and Sergei Kiriyenko, deputy prime
ministers Yegor Gaidar, Anatoly Chubais, Boris Fyodorov and Boris
Nemtsov, foreign economic relations ministers Pyotr Aven and Oleg
Davydov, Deputy Finance Minister Andrei Vavilov and CIS Executive
Secretary Boris Berezovsky, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Another member of the commission, Yuri Schchekochinkhin, said
"corruption is the engine of our society."
</P>
<P>
He called for an investigation into the disappearance of 7
billion rubles (about 304 million U.S. dollars) appropriated
through a commercial bank in 1997 for paying the ransom of Russian
servicemen held prisoner in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry is the most corrupt agency, said another
commission member, Nina Zatsepina of Popular Rule.
</P>
<P>
The commission's investigation into Black Sea and Sea of Azov
ports has resulted in the establishment, on the orders of Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, of an interdepartmental regional group
of over 140 members which has opened over 160 criminal cases, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 30 have been brought to court, over 200 people
brought to criminal justice and all the senior officials of the
Novorossiysk customs office fired, Zatsepina said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
