<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Firms Hide Safer Cigarettes Patents: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco firms have developed 57
ways to make cigarettes safer but have chosen not to use them,
according to a new report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, published by UK's Imperial Cancer Research Fund and
Action on Smoking and Health, showed that the tobacco industry had
57 U.S. patents approved for modifications that could have reduced
the chemicals in cigarettes that cause cancer, heart disease and
emphysema.
</P>
<P>
It reviewed 25 years of patents for designs to reduce some of
the cancer-causing compounds in cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
Cigarettes fitted with catalytic converters similar to those
used on cars were patented by the tobacco industry but never
developed, the report claimed.
</P>
<P>
Other patents included chemical filters to remove hydrogen
cyanide and hydrogen sulphide and acetaldehyde which could have
reduced respiratory illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Cigarettes incorporating this technology would present less of
a heart disease risk than currently-available brands, it was
claimed.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, manufacturing processes that reduced the level of
chemicals called nitrosamines in smokers' lungs could have reduced
the incidence of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
However, the tobacco firms never used those technologies
because producing safer cigarettes would have been expensive and
also an admission that the existing ones were "unsafe", the report
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
