<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Main Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- European Markets closed lower
Wednesday despite a strong dollar, with talk of a U.S.
interest rate rise and the unchanged UK rate leaving the
share prices deprived of buyers.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE-100 Index peaked at 6116 before noon, but was
soon falling and eventually closed down 13 points at
6048.3.
</P>
<P>
The strong start on the London markets was stopped in
its tracks by the Bank of England's decision to leave
interest rates unchagned.
</P>
<P>
Germany's share prices slid as a general reluctance to
enter the market was coupled with concern over the
government's planned tax reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax closed 129.32 points lower at 4688.52.
However, Insurers' share prices rose. This was due partly
to Morgan Stanley upgrading its performance forecasts for
Munich Re and Allianz.
</P>
<P>
French stock prices finished weaker, closing 37.60
points lower at 4011.03, as Wall Street slid into the red
towards the end of the European session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
