<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 600,000 Palestinians Detained in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Health Minister of the Palestinian
National Authority Riyad Za'noun said here Wednesday that more
than 600,000 Palestinians have been detained by Israel since its
occupation of Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Za'noun said in a report submitted to the Arab Health Ministers
Council that Israel still jails 2,800 Palestinians despite accords
on releasing Palestinian prisoners, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A number of agreement signed between the Palestinians and
Israel require that Israel set free Palestinian prisoners. But the
Jewish state procrastinated the implementation of the agreements,
a move that angered the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Some 350 prisoners are suffering from various kinds of illness,
50 of whom have heart diseases and kidney failure, the Palestinian
official said.
</P>
<P>
Za'noun accused Israeli authorities of using sick Palestinian
detainees in medical experiments, adding that humanitarian and
legal institutions have demanded the issue be referred to
international and judicial organizations.
</P>
<P>
Israel detains 100 children and 130 adults from Algeria, Iraq,
Jordan, Lebanon, Palestine, Sudan and Syria, who are above the age
of 45, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some 267 prisoners have spent 10 to 26 years behind bars, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Za'noun is in Cairo to attend a two-day meeting of the Arab
Health Ministers Council, which opened on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Killed, 30 Injured in U.S. Bus Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Two people were killed and over
30 others injured when a bus carrying elementary school students
home from a ski outing crashed and overturned on a narrow canyon
road in New Mexico State of the United States, said reports
reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One child and one adult died Tuesday after being thrown through
the windshield just outside Santa Fe in the state, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
"There were a lot of students walking along the roadway. They
were bleeding and crying and frantic," said Whitney Russell, who
came upon the scene moments after the accident.
</P>
<P>
The bus that crashed was one of three that was carrying
students from six local elementary schools back from the Santa Fe
Ski Area.
</P>
<P>
The wounded were treated at a nearby Hospital. Eight people
remained hospitalized Wednesday, including one child in critical
condition and another in serious, according to the reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
