<HEADLINE> China Urges End to U.S., British Military Actions in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China Wednesday urged an
immediate end to U.S. and British airstrikes against Iraq's
targets, according to a U.N. diplomat.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the United Nations Security Council was
briefed by a U.N. official on the damage to Iraq's Kirkuk pipeline
which was caused by U.S. and British airstrikes in the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, said the no-fly zones establish by the United States and
Britain were not authorized by the Security Council, and therefore
they were illegal, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Qin, who is also the Council president for the current month,
urged all parties concerned to cease immediately all military
actions so that the humanitarian programs in Iraq could be
implemented, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Russia and some other members of the Council supported China's
position, the diplomat added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
