<HEADLINE> FBI Comes to Zambia to Probe Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A team of agents of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation of the United States have arrived in
Zambia to help probe the series of bombings which rocked the
capital city of Lusaka Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day the Zambian government invited the U.S.
government to provide expert assistance in the investigation of
the explosions, which took place in six places around the city
including the Angolan embassy.
</P>
<P>
A main pipe supplying water from Kafue to Lusaka was damaged.
</P>
<P>
Asking the Unites States to send experts to Zambia to
investigate the acts of terrorism, the government also said that
it will leave the door open to other countries of goodwill to send
in experts to help in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
The bombings left one Angolan security officer dead and another
Angolan national wounded and the embassy building wrecked badly.
</P>
<P>
The explosions have also caused water shortages in most part of
the city, sending many people to fetch water from afar.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Angola has repeatedly accused Zambia of supplying
arms to the National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) rebels and threatened to take military actions against
those countries backing UNITA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
