<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Arab Committee on Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf said on Wednesday that Iraq rejects the Arab
Committee on sanctions imposed on Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency
(INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf made the remarks in a statement after member states of
the committee decided to hold a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that the committee is imbalanced and
has many contradictions in its aims and its nature, and that many
Arab countries have voiced rejection of the committee.
</P>
<P>
"These contradictions are reflected in the attitudes of some
members of the committee," Sahhaf said, adding that Saudi Arabia,
one of its members, provided facilities for U.S. and British
warplanes to commit daily aggressions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The committee, formed after Arab foreign ministers meeting in
Cairo on January 24 and entrusted with the mission of studying
how the sanctions imposed on Iraq can be lifted, is composed of
Egypt, Syria, Jordan and Yemen in addition to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers meeting fell short of Iraq's demand
of condemning the mid-December U.S.-British air strikes against
Baghdad and lifting the U.N. sanctions by Arab countries
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf argued that the committee was born under the current
weak Arab situation, therefore it cannot support Iraq's just
demands and will blur Iraq's efforts to achieve its right in
lifting the sanctions which was imposed on Iraq after its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
"This committee was born dead," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for holding another Arab meeting as soon as
possible, saying a successful Arab meeting will serve the
interests of the Arab nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
