<HEADLINE> Romania to Strengthen Cooperation in Southeast Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Romania will continue its
efforts to strengthen cooperation among the members of the
Cooperation of States in Southeastern Europe (SEE) after taking
over the presidency of the organization, said spokesperson for
Romania's Foreign Ministry Carmen Podgorean Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Beginning March 1, 1999, Romania holds the presidency of the
Cooperation of States in SEE, with Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu
as the current president. Turkey was the last holder of the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
During its term, Romania will organize the meeting of foreign
ministers, the meeting of heads of state or government and four
meetings of political directors, Podgorean told a news conference
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antalya (Turkey) recommendation by heads of
government last October, the Charter of Good Neighborliness Ties
and Stability in Southeastern Europe will be adopted at the 1999
summit.
</P>
<P>
As a current president, Romania will find new forms of
strengthening political and economic cooperation among the
participating states and will continue its efforts to strengthen
cooperation between SEE and other regional initiatives, stressed
the spokesperson for the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The organization was set up at the end of 1996, with the
participating states being Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia, the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia,
Romania and Turkey. Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina are observers.
</P>
</TEXT>
