<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Retailers Against Price Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Retailers Association of
Zimbabwe (RAZ) Wednesday said they are against introducing price
controls on goods as this will result in distortions.
</P>
<P>
RAZ chairman Bill Clarke told reporters that price control
would not resolve anything. What needed to be corrected was
management of the economy,

he said.
</P>
<P>
Clarke said the increase of 12.5 percent on the price of
cooking oil was reasonable and likely to have been too small
although it ignored the plight of consumers.
</P>
<P>
He said the increase was unavoidable due to the devaluation of
the local currency caused by "government mismanagement".
</P>
<P>
The issue of price controls, he said, was complicated because
manufacturers needed to have reasonable returns on their
investment.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarire announced
Tuesday that the government would gazette the prices of flour and
bread if millers refused to reverse the increases which they
already affected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, students of University of Zimbabwe expressed concern
 Wednesday over cooking oil price hike.
</P>
<P>
They said in a statement that consumers would suffer more as
salaries continued to be eroded.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, students at tertiary institutions are placed in
dire straits because the increase in the price of cooking oil will
inevitably lead to food price increase," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Student leader Takura Zhangazha asked the government to review
the position it has taken for the benefit of all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
