<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Jordan-Kuwait Ties Turn a New Page </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral relations between
Kuwait and Jordan turn a new page following the official visit to
Kuwait by Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah al-Khatib.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib, the highest-ranking Jordanian official to visit
Kuwait in nine years, arrived here Tuesday with the aim of
restoring ties damaged by Amman's siding with Baghdad in the 1990
Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay here, al-Khatib met with Kuwaiti Emir
Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, to whom he conveyed a message
from Jordan's new King Abdullah on issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with his Kuwaiti counterpart Sheikh Sabah
Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah on improving bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Sheikh Sabah, also Kuwait's first deputy
prime minister, said that relations between Jordan and his
country are back to normal.
</P>
<P>
"They (bilateral ties) are back to their horizons, and the
first fruit of that is the visit of my brother Abdul Ilah," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the visit will "strengthen bilateral ties and
expand them to more cooperation and coordination."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Sheikh Sabah said that Kuwait will lift its ban
on Jordanian workers. Thousands of Jordanians lost their jobs in
Kuwait as the price paid for their government's sympathy with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"There is no objection on any Jordanian willing to come to
Kuwait if he is employed here," Sheikh Sabah said.
</P>
<P>
Before concluding his visit, al-Khatib said his country's
normalization of relations with Kuwait was "a great achievement
for inter-Arab ties."
</P>
<P>
He underlined the importance of developing ties in all fields
beyond exchanges between governments.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian official expressed hope for dialog between
parliaments and social organizations in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Kuwaiti prisoners of war (POWs), allegedly
still held in Iraq, al-Khatib said that Jordanians are
sympathizing with the plight of those people.
</P>
<P>
"Jordanian people and government will spare no efforts to
support the Kuwaiti brothers in putting an end to the sufferings
of the Kuwaiti POWs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the reopening of the Jordanian embassy in
Kuwait, al-Khatib said "We do not say that the resumption of the
embassy work was a restoration of bilateral ties" which he said
have never been severed.
</P>
<P>
The embassy was closed "due to security circumstances that
prevailed during Iraq's invasion and occupation of this sisterly
state," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Jordan were almost cut off
following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. A
rapprochement process began only in May 1997 when Kuwait declared
it "likes to improve ties with all Arab countries except Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Since then the two countries have exchanged a number of middle
and high-level visits. Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister
Sheikh Saad went to Amman early February to attend the funeral of
Jordan's late King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Jordan are also moving closer in economic fields,
with bilateral trade reaching 36 million U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bodies of Killed Tourists Ready for Home: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 3 (xinhua) - British High Commissioner to Uganda
Michael Cook said Wednesday autopsies and identifications of the
British victims of

the Bwindi rebel attack have been completed and preparations are
being made to fly them home.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference here Wednesday
afternoon, adding that formalities are almost over for those who
were rescued to be repatriated.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador, who declined to release the names of the dead,
said however that there were three men and one woman.
</P>
<P>
The British High Commission has looked after even those
survivors whose countries do not have embassies in Uganda . These
people are currently receiving counseling from professionals and
comfort from each other.
</P>
<P>
Cook said the attack by Rwandan Hutu Interahamwe rebels was an
organized action. He also confirmed that the killings were not a
result of cross fire between Ugandan troops and the rebels because
there was no military contact between them.
</P>
<P>
A gang of about 150 fully armed Interahamwe rebels attacked
tourist camps in the famous Bwindi Impenetrable Forest in western
Uganda early Monday morning, abducting 32 tourists after killing
the forest warden.
</P>
<P>
Eight foreign tourists including four Britons, two Americans
and two new Zealanders were killed.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni has condemned, in the strongest terms
possible, the brutal attack on the tourists and has ordered
Ugandan troops to pursue the rebels and kill them.
</P>
<P>
 Those countries whose nationals were killed in the incident
also condemned the barbaric act of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
A team of secret agents have arrived here from the United
States to help investigate the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
