<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Official Briefs Council on Damages to Iraq's Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Kirkuk pipeline had
been shut down since Sunday evening following damage to a
communications repeater station, a U.N. official said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the United Nations Security Council on the damages to
Iraq's pipeline which was caused by the almost daily confrontation
between the United States, Britain and Iraq, Benon Sevan,
Executive Director of the United Nations office of the Iraq
Program, said oil had not flowed to Ceyhan of Turkey since late
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
But because there were some 2.4 million barrels of oil in
storage at Ceyhan, there had been no interruption in loading it
aboard ships, Sevan said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to start loading tomorrow another ship with 1.8
million barrels, and on the Iraqi side, they are trying very hard
to expedite the repairs to the repeater station," Sevan said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi technicians were working on restoring the
communications links severed by damage to the repeater station.
</P>
<P>
"If communications links are restored, pumping of oil could
resume almost immediately," Sevan added.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline from Iraq's Kirkuk to Turkey's Ceyhan carries half
the oil Iraq is permitted to export under the terms of United
Nations Security Council resolutions establishing the oil for food
program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
