<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs of
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel Electric Company and the Environment
Ministry have jointly inaugurated an innovative facility that uses
solar and wind energy to desalt sea water.
</P>
<P>
With a budget of 120,000 U.S. dollars, the facility at Kibbutz
Ma'agan Michael produces enough drinking water to meet 50 people's
needs.
</P>
<P>
The system is able to produce drinking water at locations
connected to electricity grids, or those undeveloped areas, as in
many developing countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's metals and electrical sector registered a
4 percent drop in local sales in 1998, totaling 28.5 billion
U.S. dollars, while exports increased by 14 percent, reaching 3.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exports of engines and electrical equipment grew by
20.6 percent as compared with those of the previous year,
transportation vehicles by 25.6 percent, basic metals and metal
products by 4.2 percent, machinery and equipment by 13.6 percent,
according to the Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's export volume of polished diamonds
totaled 284 million dollars in February, compared to 318 million
dollars in the same period of last year, down 10.9 percent, the
Ministry of Industry and Trade said.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry predicted a recovery in the diamond
industry, including an increase in purchases in the world's
diamond exchanges and a 43 percent increase in the imports of
rough diamonds in February compared to February last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. remains the major importer of Israeli polished
diamonds, which imports 61 percent of the total, followed by Hong
Kong, accounting for 9 percent, Japan 8 percent, Belgium 6 percent
and Switzerland 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dubai -- The UAE Airline, owned by the Dubai municipal
administration signed a funding contract with banks on the
delivery of 142.9 million euro (about 157.5 million U.S. dollars)
to buy two Airbus carriers.
</P>
<P>
The two aircraft are among the 17 Airbus 330/200 planes to be
delivered to the company this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
