<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dumas Accused by Ex-Girlfriend of Sharing Bribes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Former French Foreign Minister
Roland Dumas was accused Wednesday by his ex-girlfriend, Christine
Deviers-Joncour, of sharing the bribes she received from the Elf
oil company.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Joncour to formally charge Dumas
since the scandal involving the present president of France's
highest legal authority, the Council of State, erupted one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
During a testimony with two judges in charge of investigating
the alleged acts of corruption of Dumas when he was foreign
minister under President Francois Mitterrand, Joncour said that
she used the money from Elf to buy Greek antiques for Dumas in
1990.
</P>
<P>
She and Dumas went to an auction sale in a Parisian hotel in
December 1990 and spent 300,000 francs (50,000 U.S. dollars) in
buying 12 Greek statuettes.
</P>
<P>
The money was sent by former Elf president Alfred Sirven, who
asked Joncour to buy these antiques as "gifts" for Dumas, said
Joncour.
</P>
<P>
Sirven is believed to be hiding in Switzerland and is under two
international arrest mandates.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Rene Farthouat, a defense lawyer of Dumas, immediately
denied the accusation and said that Dumas was not aware of the
origin of the money used in purchasing the statuettes.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Dumas only got five statuettes and Joncour
kept seven others for herself.
</P>
<P>
Joncour was suspected to have received 66 million francs (11
million U.S. dollars) of bribes from the Elf from 1989 till 1993.
</P>
<P>
She was believed to have played a role in the agreement by the
French government to sell three fregates to Taiwan in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Elf reportedly paid her commissions for arranging the deal on
behalf of the producer of the fregates, state-owned defense and
electronics group Thomson SA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
