<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Places Health Central for Development in 21st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO) said on Wednesday that it will place health
central in the program of development in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The director general of WHO, Gro Harlem Brundtland, told a
seminar here that "my vision is that to put the issue of health
at the core of international development agenda," which will
attract more world attention to women's health.
</P>
<P>
"There is no development without sustainable development," and
it is crucial to educate young women and their children and to
better the environment for the future of humanity, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The 20th century has been a century of remarkable progress for
the rights of women, progress in political rights, progress for
the right to take responsibility for our own lives," she said.
</P>
<P>
But there is also other side for the rights of women at the
moment, she said.
</P>
<P>
Millions and millions of women are denied the political right,
the fundamental human rights, the right to take responsibility for
their own lives, and "millions and millions of women lack the
right to lead a healthy life," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Too many women are infected with HIV, and too many women died
of AIDS," she said. "Too many women do not control their own
lives, do not have the means or environment to take control of
their lives and that of their children."
</P>
<P>
At present, "poverty still has a gender bias," she said. "More
than two out of three of the 1.3 billion living in poverty are
women."
</P>
<P>
Brundtland took office on July 21, 1998. Over the past six
months since her election to the position of WHO's
director-general, she has introduced structural changes in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was co-organized by the Global Alliance for Women's
Health and the International Council of Women.
</P>
<P>
The Global Alliance for Women's Health, a non-governmental
organization in special consultative status with the U.N. Economic
and Social Council is committed to advancing women's health in all
stages of life and at all policy levels through health promotion,
education, advocacy and program implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
