<HEADLINE> U.S. Defends Its Military Actions in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
defended its military actions in Iraq, saying it was acting to
protect the vulnerable population of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council Wednesday morning was
briefed on the damage to Iraq's pipeline caused by the almost
daily airstrikes against Iraq's targets by the United States and
Britain. China, Russia and other Council members condemned the two
countries and urged an immediate end to the military actions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, U.S. Ambassador to the Untied Nations
Nancy Soderberg said, "U.S. forces in the region are acting to
protect the vulnerable population of Iraq and any action we take
is aimed simply to protect our own forces. U.S. pilots have been
increasingly targeted."
</P>
<P>
Soderberg denied her country targeted Iraq's pipeline and said
neither it nor pumping station had been hit.
</P>
<P>
"The area that was hit was in our belief part of the Iraqi air
defense system, the communications area. The Iraqi command and
control is part of the area that is threatening our pilots and we
will continue to move in our self-defense," she added.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline from Iraq's Kirkuk to Turkey's Ceyhan has been
shut down since Sunday due to damage to a communications repeater
station. The pipeline carries half the oil Iraq is permitted to
export under the terms of the United Nations Security Council
resolutions establishing the oil-for-food program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
