<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Encouraged by Progress on Kosovo Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that it was encouraged by good progress the ethnic
Albanians had made toward approval for a peace deal on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
""there's good progress with the Kosovars," White House
spokesman David Leavy said. "There's indications that they are
going to officially embrace the political settlement and we are
encouraged by that and we're going to move forward to lock that
in."
</P>
<P>
"I'm told that there has been a very positive session,"
involving special U.S. Kosovo envoy Christopher Hill and the
ethnic Albanians, Leavy told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Leavy said there had been preliminary discussion about inviting
a delegation representing Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas to
Washington for talks.
</P>
<P>
Washington's strategy is first to persuade the ethnic Albanians
into accepting a peace deal that would give Kosovo substantial
autonomy but would fall short of the independence they seek.
</P>
<P>
It would then increase pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to agree the deployment of NATO peacekeepers in the
province for implementation of the peace accord. If Milosevic
disagrees, NATO would launch air strikes against Serbian military
targets.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to come into compliance and end this crisis is
for Milosevic to sign a new peace agreement... and allow a NATO
military presence," Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
About 430 NATO strike and support planes, including 260 U.S.
jets, are poised to carry out orders for military action once
Belgrade refuses NATO's coercive demand for its military presense
in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
