<HEADLINE> Beijing Strives to Improve Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Municipal Government
launched the second stage of its anti-air-pollution campaign by
proposing a set of 28 measures today in an effort to reduce the
volume of air pollutants in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital is one of the world's ten most polluted
cities. Government officials at all levels in Beijing, including
Mayor Liu Qi, today signed a letter of responsibility promising a
significant improvement in air quality by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting today, Mayor Liu said the city has
achieved successful results in the control of air pollution thanks
to the introduction of 18 measures since last December to control
local air pollution caused by coal burning, auto exhaust emissions,
and dust and suspended particles.
</P>
<P>
A test has shown that the amount of nitride and oxide in
Beijing's air dropped by 10 percent this January compared with the
same month last year, and the sulfur dioxide density fell 17
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The second-stage objective for pollution control aims at
consolidating the achievement of the first stage. The new measures
will emphasize construction site management, the increased use of
natural gas, and auto-exhaust emissions control, Liu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
