<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's 15 Major Banks Seek 60 Billion U.S. Dollars in Public Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan's 15 major banks on Thursday
applied a total of 7.46 trillion yen (60.8 billion U.S. dollars)
in public funds to replenish their capital bases.
</P>
<P>
The financial Reconstruction Commission (FRC), a government
body charged with recovering the health of the country's ailing
banking sector, is expected to give the go-ahead to the
applications on March 12 and infuse new capital into the banks on
March 30.
</P>
<P>
Under the Japanese government's banking sector bail-out program
enacted last October, 25 trillion yen (203.8 billion dollars) in
public money has been made available to recapitalize banks whose
coffers have been depleted by writing off non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Japanese banks had shown reluctance to lend to small and medium-
size companies, which constrained the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
By helping the banks, the Japanese government hopes to rebuild
a healthy financial system, in which small and medium-size
companies will be able to borrow funds more freely.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's applications followed the FRC's preliminary approval
February 12 for the financial institutions to take out public
money under the bank clean-up scheme.
</P>
<P>
The fund injections will take the form of the government's
purchasing of preferred shares exchangeable for common stock and
taking out subordinated loans from the 15 banks.
</P>
<P>
The 15 banks include eight "city" banks with nationwide
networks -- Asahi Bank, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Daiwa Bank, Fuji
Bank, Sakura Bank, Sanwa Bank, Sumitomo Bank and Tokai Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
