<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban, Opposition to Meet on March 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi said here Thursday that the Afghan
Taliban militia and the opposition will hold a meeting in
Ashgabat, Turkmenistan, on March 10.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Thursday afternoon, Brahimi, who
arrived here last week on his fresh peace mission, urged the
militia and the opposition to go to the Ashgabat meeting in a
spirit of "compromise and constructiveness."
</P>
<P>
"This is the real chance and I hope they will not waste it," he
said. "On behalf of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, I appeal to
the two parties to go to the talks with the spirit of compromise,
understanding, patience and constructiveness."
</P>
<P>
"I very much hope that they will give this opportunity a chance
and explore the possibility of achieving peace and indeed
achieving their ends through peaceful means rather than resorting
to war," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the war has not led to the solution of their
problems and the two Afghan delegations should capitalize on the
new opportunity.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the Afghan rival parties is to take place
in the capital of Turkmenistan against the backdrop of hectic
diplomatic efforts by the United Nations and the Organization of
the Islamic Conference backed by Afghanistan's immediate
neighbors, the envoy said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is encouraging the Six Plus Two group to
hold its proposed meeting in Uzbek capital of Tashkent later this
year for the restoration of durable peace in the war-torn
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The group comprises Afghanistan's six immediate neighboring
countries -- Pakistan, Iran, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan
and China -- plus the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The group has been holding discussions in New York on how to
help restore lasting peace in Afghanistan, Brahimi said,
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to the neighboring countries to extend their
wholehearted support to the Ashgabat negotiations and encourage
the Afghans to achieve a positive conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the U.N. staff's return to
Afghanistan, Brahimi said negotiations with the Taliban on
security concerns are under way and he hoped the assessment of the
report about the talks will be positive.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. staff will go back to Afghanistan if the result of the
discussions with the Taliban is positive, he added.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi made a one-day visit to Afghanistan on Sunday and held
talks with Taliban leaders in the capital of Kabul. He later
described the talks as "very constructive."
</P>
<P>
The special envoy will leave here Friday for Tehran, Iran, and
he will also go to Central Asian states. He is expected to have
discussions with leaders of these countries with the focus on the
Afghan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
