<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Quits European Table Tennis League Next Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Sweden will withdraw from next
season's European Table Tennis League to protest the way the
competition is run, a senior table tennis official said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to change the way the league's competition system so
far, but the European Table Tennis Federation(ETTF) turned a deaf
ear to our opinion, so we have to opt to quit the league next
season," said Orjan Nilsson, president of Sweden National Table
Tennis Management Committee, Wednesday night,
</P>
<P>
Nilsson said the Sweden Table Tennis Association made the
decision a month ago for the ETTF declined to take its proposal of
adopting the knockout system to slash the number of games in the
league.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the league have to put themselves through the
group stages and then qualifiers before they finally reach the
finals.
</P>
<P>
The league profile has been lowered for the big number of games,
which scared many well-known players withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Big guns such as Jan-Ove Walderner and Joegen Persson, both
from Sweden, have skipped the event since last year, while Germany
and France are sending their second-string players to take part in
the tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
