<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Writer Bids Farewell to Century-Long Literary Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The death of veteran Chinese
writer Bing Xin, who passed away for heart failure after spending
four years and five months in hospital on February 28 at the age
of 99, has hit the headlines in all the major Chinese media.
</P>
<P>
An activist among the students in the May 4th Movement in 1919
which called for democracy and freedom in China, Bing Xin began to
impress literary circles with her novels questioning the
unfairness of society and the way out for her generation.
</P>
<P>
As one of the earliest translators of Tagore's poems, she began
to write the free lyrical verses with a sentimental and beautiful
style and soon many followed her example.
</P>
<P>
Another masterpiece of hers is To Young Readers, a series of
letters covering nearly half a century, including memories of her
time in Wellesley College in the States as a literature
postgraduate, her meditations on the everlasting themes of life in
the Chinese Anti-Japanese War, and her advice on finding a better
future after the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Bing Xin returned to New China in 1951 with her husband Wu
Wenzao, a Ph.D. of Columbia University and one of the pioneers of
Chinese sociology and anthropology.
</P>
<P>
Wu was tagged a "rightist" in 1957, a derogatory name for anti-
socialist intellectuals and died in 1985.
</P>
<P>
"Now only you can help him to survive this difficult period,"
Premier Zhou Enlai once said to Bing Xin.
</P>
<P>
Bing Xin was ordered to clean the toilets for the Chinese
Writer's Association for two years.
</P>
<P>
"Life is never free of setbacks," Bing Xin often told her
daughters Wu Qing and Wu Bing, who are now professors with
Beijing Foreign Studies University.
</P>
<P>
Just before US president Richard Nixon's historical visit to
China in 1972 Wu Wenzao and Bing Xin were called back from the
countryside and took part in translating Six Crises by Nixon and
later Outline of History by H.G. Wells.
</P>
<P>
Bing Xin was applauded by intelligentsia and the public for her
outspokenness when she was in her 80s. She wrote quite some social
critiques calling for more input into education and better
conditions for intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
Many readers responded by writing to her saying they were in
tears, praising her as the conscience of society, according to
Bing Xin's eldest son Wu Ping, an architect and a graduate from
the prestigious Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Bing Xin once donated 90,000 yuan (about 10,800 U.S. dollars to
a foundation for the education of Chinese rural women. And in her
will she donated all her savings to help the schooling of rural
children and the Contemporary Chinese Literary Museum.
</P>
<P>
Heart-broken by the flood victims last summer, she donated 12,
000 yuan (about 1,400 US dollars) to the homeless.
</P>
<P>
A long-cherished wish of Bing Xin was to write a novel on the
Sino-Japanese War of 1894-1895, when her father, a general on a
Qing Dynasty warship, swam back home after the miserable defeat of
China.
</P>
<P>
Bing Xin couldn't help crying, thinking of the pains and
humiliations that her father and all the nation had endured and
had to cancel the writing plan because of her deep emotional
involvement.
</P>
<P>
As a supporter of euthanasia, the veteran writer had always
regarded death as a natural thing. "I came to this world silently,
and I also want a quiet good-bye," said this prestigious writer
who has eyewitnessed the vicissitudes of the whole century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Holds First Press Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) --The Second Session of the National
People's Congress will be held between March 5-15 in Beijing,
according to the session's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"It is an important session to be held at an important time and
a major event in the political life of the Chinese people,"
Spokesman Zeng Jianhui said at the session's first press
conference held here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Zeng briefed reporters on the session's agenda and the
legislative work of the Standing Committee of the Ninth National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee of this term pays special attention
to the quality of legislation and has introduced new ways for the
enactment of laws, he said. It solicits views and opinions about
laws from all social circles and publishes law drafts on
newspapers to get people's views on them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Law makers, including NPC Standing Committee Chairman Li Peng,
have made frequent fact-finding tours to grassroots units, where
they have done research and obtained first-hand materials that
have a bearing on legislation.
</P>
<P>
"Now drafts for some important laws and decisions have to go
through three rounds of examinations and deliberations by the NPC
Standing Committee before their enactment,compared with two rounds
in the past," Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen the legislature's supervisory role, the NPC
Standing Committee sent six work groups to localities in the past
year to check on the implementation of six laws and decisions. A
feed-back mechanism has been put in place to end non-enforcement
or slack enforcement of laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee will speed up drafting a law on
supervision, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a subordinate institution of the National People's Congress,
the Preparatory Committee for the Macao Special Administrative
Region (PCMSAR) is working at high gear and in good order.
</P>
<P>
The just concluded PCMSAR's 6th meeting produced a namelist of
candidates for a Selecting Committee for the first Macao SAR
government. The Selecting Committee will be officially voted into
being at the preparatory committee's next meeting, Zeng said.
</P>
</TEXT>
