<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Second Resettlement Program On Yangtze River under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 4(Xinhua) -- China has started its second
population resettlement program along the Yangtze River to make
way for the Three Gorges Dam project.
</P>
<P>
The first one is still going on along the upper reaches of the
river. The second involves moving nearly twice the number of
people, or about 2 million. Premier Zhu Rongji calls it "a
strategic move that follows the laws of nature".
</P>
<P>
The filling in of wetlands for farm use has been cited as the
main cause of the flood disasters on the river in recent years by
the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Chinese Academy of Engineering,
who have explained that, since the 1950s, the amount of arable
land has grown by 9,000 sq km, 6,700 sq km of that from filled in
lakes. The present size of these catch basins along the river is
just 40 percent of their size in 1949, the year of national
liberation.
</P>
<P>
When the program is completed, the floodwater capacity of the
Yangtze will increase by over 10 billion cu.m., nearly half of the
projected storage capacity of the Three Gorges Dam. Eighty percent
of the 940,000 people that were left homeless by the disastrous
floods last summer have moved to new homes. In the next three to
five years, more than a million people in Hunan, Hubei, Jiangsu,
Anhui and Jiangxi provinces will be moved out of low lying areas.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new settlements are just a few kilometers away from
the old residences. One farmer explains that he can still do farm
his land as usual, but during the flood seasons it will be covered
with water. Then it can be used again when the water recedes.
</P>
<P>
"One of the program's primary aims is to deal with the threat
to people's lives," says Li Antian, director of the Water Resource
Ministry's Yangtze River Water Conservation Committee.
</P>
<P>
In the past, most flood control efforts involved reinforcing
embankments. The central government has used 4 billion yuan for
that over the past four decades and a great deal of labor, but
with little effect, Li says. Last year's floods alone caused 200
billion yuan worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
Farmers were aroused and organized to mend and reinforce dykes
in the cold winter time and to fight floods in the hot summer
almost every year and it cost a great deal of manpower and money,"
says Yang Daozhou, an official in a village at Shenhuangzhou on
the outskirts of Shishou city, where more than 1,000 residents
have been displaced. He says that the new village is taking the
shape of a small town.
</P>
<P>
The central government has allocated 2.5 billion yuan for this
program, or 15,000 yuan per household. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ninth NPC Receives Many Letters of Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) received and handled more
than 60,000 letters of complaints from the people in the past year.
</P>
<P>
According to an office under the General Office of the NPC
Standing Committee handling letters from and calls by people who
lodged their complaints, it also received more than 11,000 people
who came to the office to voice their complaints.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, handled many
letters from the people in the past year. He also urged NPC
deputies to answer the letters and calls from the people in time.
</P>
<P>
As a result, workers of the office have helped people solve a
lot of practical difficulties and problems, and thus defused some
social contradictions, protected their legal rights and interests
and promoted the social stability, according to the office.
</P>
