<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Enterprise Reform Must Rely on Working Class, Wei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior leader of the ruling
Communist Party of China (CPC) called for relying wholeheartedly
on the working class when reforming and developing state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, a member of the Standing Committee of the CPC
Central Committee Political Bureau, made the call here today at a
group discussion attended by members of the Ninth National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference in session here since yesterday.
</P>
<P>
A major task in 1999 is to push ahead with reform and
development of state-owned enterprises, he said. "The Party's
principle of depending on the working class wholeheartedly should
be carried out unswirvingly" in the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wei is also a member of the CPC Central Committee Secretariat
and president of the All-China Federation of Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
This year, Wei said, efforts will be made to reinforce the
workers' conference system with emphasis to be placed on making
factory affairs public. The system is a basic one with Chinese
characteristics and is one of the political advantages of the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The leading unionist said that workers have the right to be
informed, a right that belongs to them as masters of the
enterprise. "Being informed is a precondition for the promotion of
enterprise reform through relying on workers and staff," he said.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the principle of relying wholeheartedly on
the working class should be combined with efforts to build a
modern enterprise system for state enterprises, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the deepening of state enterprise reform
should be integrated with the strengthening of a supervisory
mechanism in such firms. Representatives of workers and staff
should sit on the board of directors and board of supervisors, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
