<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Suggest Rules for Gov't Procurement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the Second Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) said that China has to
establish a legislation governing government procurement as soon
as possible so as to meet the need of the socialist market-driven
economy.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhongli from the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences said
that the current practice of allocating purchasing funds to
various government institutions has caused such problems as blind
and duplicated purchases and unfairness in competition.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Chinese government administrative
institutions spend 700 billion yuan on procurement every year.
</P>
<P>
The practice of allowing individual institutions to decide what
to buy incurred losses to government funds, according to Lu Xueyi,
director of the Sociology Institute of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
He said that the practice lacks transparency and leaves
loopholes for a small number of people to pocket government money
when they handle the procurement.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, Chongqing city, Hebei and Shandong provinces have
initiated government purchases in certain fields on a trial basis.
Now a dozen provincial governments in China have introduced the
way of government purchase.
</P>
<P>
Deputies from Shandong province said that the provincial
government is to expand the scope of government purchase from cars
and computers to most other fields.
</P>
<P>
They said that China needs a law or regulations governing the
government procurement.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen city, a special economic zone in south China's
Guangdong province, has passed a set of regulations governing its
procurement earlier this year, the first of its kind in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
