<HEADLINE> Share Prices End Higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed higher on
Singapore Stock Market Thursday, with the benchmark Straits Times
Index (STI) up 17.6 points to 1,433.41 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume increased to 131.64 million units worth 225.03
million Singapore dollars (about 129.75 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers led losers by 173 to 69 with 105 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was the 11.45 million stock parcel by GES that
was transacted at 0.3 Singapore dollars per share. Hotung was the
second most heavily traded stock with 9.17 million units done.
Ipco w02 was the next with 8.49 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
CityDev was the biggest gainer of the day that surged up 25
cents to 7.15 Singapore dollars. It was followed by Bukit Sem that
ran up 20 cents to close at 8.7 Singapore dollars. DBS F rose by
20 cents to close at 13 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Sp Bldg headed the descent of the day with a
loss of 25 cents to end at 1 Singapore dollar. Elec&AMP;E sank 20
cents to end at 4.78 U.S. dollars. GP Bat lost 14 cents to finish
at 2.8 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
The market started on a weak note following a slide on Wall
Street Wednesday and interest in small-capital counters gave some
support to the broader market.
</P>
<P>
Property Stocks led the day's rise on rumors that local bank
OCBC will lower its prime lending rate and the belief that
residential property prices have bottomed out, which gave a boost
to the sector's share prices. 
</P>
