<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Protect Northeastern Black Soil Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China will make further efforts to
protect the fertile black soil area in the northeastern part of
the country, legislators from northeast China's Jilin Province
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The northeastern region each year produces some 35 million
tons of commercial grains and is therefore reputed as China's 'big
barn'. The black soil area in Jilin and Heilongjiang provinces
provides the region's best farmland," said Liu Xiang, a Jilin
deputy to the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Liu, a research fellow with the Jilin Provincial Institute of
Agricultural Sciences, is here for the upcoming annual session of
the Ninth NPC, scheduled to open tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1970s, Liu said, the Chinese government has
taken a series of measures, such as planting trees to form shelter
forest belts, to maintain natural conditions in the black soil
area.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, however, part of the land in this area has
shown signs of deterioration as a result of long-time cultivation,
with the land's content of organic substance and its fertility
level keeping on dropping, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, natural shields for the black soil area,
which mainly refer to natural forests in the Changbai Mountains to
the east of the area and the large area of grassland to its west,
have gradually diminished due to excessive logging and
desertification.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shaoming, another Jilin lawmaker, said that his province
is now making active efforts to persuade local farmers to abandon
traditional farming techniques and turn to an ecology-friendly
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"We encourage farmers to adopt crop rotation and replace
chemical fertilizers with organic manure," said Yang, who is also
head of the Jilin Provincial Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The province also plans to plant more trees in the shelter
forest belts, gradually cut the size of the logging industry in
the Changbai Mountains and improve the ecological environment in
the western grassland area to prevent any further loss of land to
desert, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Once these measures take effect, grain production in the black
soil area can be further raised," he said. "We expect that grain
output in northeast China will increase by at least 18 million
tons by the year 2005, which can feed half of the 90 million
people to be born in China over the same period." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
