<HEADLINE> Dollar Gains, Stocks Inch Up in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar climbed against the
yen in Tokyo on Thursday due to the fall in Japanese interest
rates and increasing expectations that the Bank of Japan (BOJ)
will take steps to further ease monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 122.57-60 yen, its lowest point
so far this year, at closing, up from 121.93-96 yen at opening and
from 121.80-90 yen in New York late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the overnight call rate to near zero persuaded
market participants, particularly overseas players, to sell the
yen against the dollar, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On the stock market, share prices moved marginally higher, led
mainly by exporters, which were bought on the U.S. dollar's
advance against the yen.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained 13.09 points, or 0.09
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 14,183.45.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 5.30 points or 0.48 percent to 1,105.
11.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section declined to 389.33 million shares
from Wednesday's 395.38 million shares. Despite the overall gain,
losers surpassed gainers 585 to 566, with 151 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
