<HEADLINE> Fund Collects 120 Million Yuan for Tibet's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Aid Tibet Fund has collected
over 120 million yuan (14 million U.S. dollars) in the past 11
years for launching some 420 cultural, educational and welfare
projects within the autonomous region and some other areas
inhabited by Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman at the fund's headquarters here, the
non-government fund collected 23 million yuan (2.7 million dollars)
in 1998 for the building of over 30 social development projects.
</P>
<P>
Those funds focused on eye-sight restoration for Tibet's
cataract patients last year during which more than 2,000 Tibetans
had their eyesight restored thanks to 12 million yuan (1.4 million
dollars) provided by the fund.
</P>
<P>
It also offered funds for building primary schools in the
region's most remote counties, the protection of cultural relics,
rural clinics and running technical training courses for rural
women and launching aid-the-poor projects.
</P>
<P>
When the Ngari, Xigaze, Nagqu prefectures were hit by
snowstorms last winter and southern Tibet was hit by heavy floods
last summer the fund managed to collect over 1.7 million yuan (200,
000 dollars) for disaster relief, on top of relief funds from the
central government.
</P>
<P>
The new funds will be spent on aid-the-poor and eye-sight
restoration programs this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
