<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong 1999-2000 Budget Wins Wide Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The 1999-2000 Budget unveiled
Wednesday by Hong Kong's Financial Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen
received wide applauds from different sectors of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Trade Development Council welcomed the
Budget's focus on strengthening Hong Kong's fundamental and long-
term competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"It's Hong Kong facing reality, standing up and telling the
world in very specific terms how we're going to make ourselves
more attractive as the region's international business hub," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the measures and initiatives announced would
lobster Hong Kong's lead in traditional areas of strength, such as
financial services and help move the economy into new business
frontiers.
</P>
<P>
The Securities and Futures Commission (SFC) fully supports the
Government in its radical reform of Kong Kong's securities and
futures market. The Financial Secretary announced Wednesday that
Hong Kong will merge its two exchanges, the Stock Exchange of Hong
Kong and the Hong Kong Futures Exchange, and their associated
clearing houses, into an eventually listed commercial entity.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Sheng, SFC chairman, said: "In the face of global
competition, we need to consolidate and upgrade our competitive
capacity. The SFC believes that through implementation of this
reform Hong Kong's market infrastructure will be well placed to
meet the competitive challenges of the new millennium."
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong, the Hong Kong Futures Exchange,
and Hong Kong Clearing all welcomed and supported the proposed
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Retailer &AMP; Tourism Services of Hong Kong
applauded the government's plan to build a Disney theme park, a
major initiative to boost Hong Kong's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
"It will enhance the attractiveness of Hong Kong as a tourist
destination and stimulate the retail and restaurant industry. It
will also benefit Hong Kong's economy in the long term," said the
Association's chairman Frank Lee.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is the second largest foreign exchange earner in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Henry Tang, chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries,
said: "We are particularly pleased that the Government will set up
a special Task Force to consider how best to remove restrictions
on mainland scientists and highly-skilled technologists entering
Hong Kong to work."
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the reduction in re-export declaration by half,
from 0.05 percent to 0.025, as well as a 10 percent rebate on the
1997-1998 final assessments of salaries, profits and property
taxes," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Both measures will help to relieve the present credit crunch
experienced by many of Hong Kong's small and medium enterprises
and should also encourage more investment into Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
The financial secretary Wednesday presented to the Legislative
Council the Budget, putting forward a string of bold initiatives
to help relieve immediate economic pain, strengthen economic
foundations and prepare Hong Kong for the new millennium. The
budget is the second one of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
