<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Reiterates Commitment to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has reiterated that his government will continue to
support the international community's efforts in battling
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Chissano reiterated the commitment here Wednesday when meeting
Robert S. Mcnamara, Chairman of the Global Coalition for Africa ,
an international anti-corruption organization.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed means of fighting corruption in
Mozambique and other African countries, Noticias newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mcnamara reviewed the significant progress his organization
has made, and said that it has suggested the World Bank join the
anti-corruption campaign by setting terms in contracts while
granting loans to projects.
</P>
<P>
Mcnamara briefed the president on an anti-corrutption
agreement passed by the Paris-based Organization for Economic
Co-operation and Development (OECD). He said the agreement, which
took effective last week, has included clauses like avoiding
signing illegal contracts with industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Social and Economic Affairs, Eneas Comiche,
said during the talks that Mozambican government has been firm in
fighting corruption. He said the loopholes should be stemmed in
the course of purchasing commodities and privatization.
</P>
<P>
Comiche revealed that the government is taking a series of
measures against corruption, such as starting revenue reforms and
increasing the salaries of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
World Bank resident representative was also present at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Mcnamara will also meet parliament speaker, entrepreneurs,
religious leaders, journalists whose roles are indispensible to
the war against corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
