<HEADLINE> Sino-US Security Seminar Held (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 4 (XINHUA) -- The second Sino-United States
Security Seminar, jointly sponsored by China's Foundation for
International Strategic Studies (FISS), the US-based Harvard
University and Stanford University, was held over the last four
days in Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang province.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was attended by such VIPs from both countries as
FISS's senior consultant Wang Daohan, ex-Chinese ambassador to the
US Li Daoyu, and top US military officials headed by former
defense secretary William Perry. The first was convened in Hawaii
last year.
</P>
<P>
All the delegates agreed that in 1999 Sino-US diplomatic ties,
which were established 20 years ago , have entered a new era of
development as both countries are making efforts to enhance
bilateral dialogues through various flexible channels, and seeking
common ground while reserving divergence, so as to play
constructive roles in stabilizing bilateral ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Security Seminar Held (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese delegates pointed out that at the present stage,
factors affecting stability and security are far from being
diminished either within the regional or the global sphere.
Moreover, regional turmoil and conflicts are deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
The key to solving these problems is to establish a kind of
active and equal multi-lateral security co-operation so as to
dissolve contradictions through mutual trust and understanding.
</P>
<P>
The resort to unilateral efforts and brutal interference are
not helpful to the fundamental solution of any hostility or crisis,
they noted.
</P>
<P>
The delegates stressed that the Taiwan issue is the center of
Sino-US relations. Both the arms sales to Taiwan and the inclusion
of Taiwan into the theater missile defense system will severely
harm the stability of the region, and finally threaten bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side called on the U.S. to pay full attention to
the issue and take appropriate measures to achieve a final
solution.
</P>
<P>
The US delegation holds that consensus exceeds divergence, and
co-operation surpasses contradictions between the two countries.
China is getting increasingly constructive and responsibility-
conscious in both regional and international affairs, and the U.S.
is not willing to - in fact it is impossible - to sever its co-
operation with China. Also, a sound U.S-China relationship is
conductive to the reform and development cause that China is now
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
They affirmed that the U.S. will neither participate nor
interfere in relations across the Taiwan straits, and welcome any
efforts that are conducive to a peaceful reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 48 Parties to Contest June Election in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Commission on
Elections Thursday announced that it is recommending 48 political
parties to contest in the June 7 general election.
</P>
<P>
Commission chairman Nurcholis Madjid made the announcement
after a meeting with Home Affairs Minister Syarwan Hamid here to
submit the results of the team's verification of the registered
parties' qualifications.
</P>
<P>
The 48 parties include the ruling Golkar (Functional Group),
the Indonesian Democratic Party, the United Development Party, the
Indonesian Democratic Party for the People's Struggle, the
National Awakening Party, the Justice and Unity Party, and the
National Mandate Party.
</P>
<P>
Nurcholis said his team had carried out the factual and
administrative verification of more than a hundred parties which
had registered at the Attorney General's Office on February 22-27
and March 2-3.
</P>
<P>
To determine party eligibility, team members visited provinces
set as the verification targets from February 22 to March 3.
</P>
<P>
The new political laws determine that political parties
eligible to take part in the June 7 general election must have
chapters in at least 9 provinces with executive boards, as well as
having regional boards in at least 50 percent of the provinces'
regencies or municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The June election will elect a new House of Representatives,
whose members will be part of the 700-strong People's Consultative
Assembly, the nation's highest legislative body, which will select
the next president.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party elections are one of the political reforms
launched by President B.J. Habibie's administration.
</P>
<P>
Under former president Soeharto, who was forced down on May 21
last year, only three parties were allowed to contest the
elections.
They were the Golkar, the United Development Party and the
Indonesian Democratic Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New ILO Chief Takes Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Juan Somavia of Chile took office
here Thursday to become the first representative from the southern
hemisphere to head the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed internationally to promote open societies and
open economies," said Somavia, who was elected by the ILO
Governing Body on March 23, 1998. "That consensus will not hold if
real benefits for ordinary people and their families are not put
into the equation."
</P>
<P>
Unlike other United Nations agencies, ILO has a tripartite
structure involving governments, employers and workers.
</P>
<P>
"I have the responsibility to modernize and help steer the
tripartite structure to make ILO values prevail in the new global
realities," said Somavia, the ninth Director-General of the Geneva-
based ILO since its founding in 1919,.
</P>
<P>
ILO has been the source of such industrial society hallmarks as
the eight-hour working day, maternity protection, child labor laws
and a whole range of policies promoting workplace safety and
peaceful industrial relations.
</P>
<P>
Born on April 21, 1941, Somavia earned degrees in law and
economics from the Catholic University of Chile and the University
of Paris. He is an attorney by profession and has had a long and
distinguished career in civil and international affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollars Weighed Down by Yen Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A struggling Japanese yen and
historically low commodity prices weighed down on the Australian
dollar Thursday, with the domestic currency shedding nearly half a
U.S. cent.
</P>
<P>
MMS Standard &AMP; Poor's currency strategist Alex Douglas said
commodity prices stuck around 24-year lows continued to drag the
local unit down and a rally in U.S. dollar/yen helped erode
Wednesday's GDP-inspired gains.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading the Australian dollar was buying 62.09
U.S. cents, from Wednesday night's close of 62.53.
</P>
<P>
During the day it hit a high of 62.30 U.S. cents and fell to a
low of 62.06.
</P>
<P>
Douglas said the U.S. dollar during afternoon trading rallied
to a high of 122.78 Japanese yen, closing at 122.34 yen from
121.00 previously. "That was what triggered a bit of selling in
Aussie," he said.
</P>
<P>
Douglas also noted that a continued slump in a leading
commodity index was having an ongoing impact on the Australian
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Commodity Research Bureau (CRB) Index closed Wednesday
night at 184.05 points, down 0.41. "In historical terms it's at
its 24-year lows," Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 0.5713 euro from 0.5724 and
the local note was also trading at 75.89 Japanese yen from 75.53.
</P>
</TEXT>
