<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The trial of Dinko Sakic, 77, former head of the
concentration camp of Jasenovac under the fascist regime of
Croatia during World War II, is due to open on Thursday in Zagreb.
Sakic, who was held responsible for the death of tens of thousands
of Serbs, Jews and Gypgsies, regrets nothing, while Croatia
remains a country which has difficulty in facing up to its past.
</P>
<P>
-- NATO has welcomed the announcement by Kosovo Albanians,
including the Kosovo Liberation Army, to sign the peace agreement
presented by the six-nation Contact Group. NATO secretary general
Javier Solana also appealed to the Serbs on Wednesday to follow
the suit, and warned that the remaining time before the resumption
of talks on Kosovo in France on March 15 is not for preparing war
but for cooperation and the search for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The sex scandal of the White House involving Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky has turned into a real business, as the former
White House intern has earned at least two million U.S. dollars by
granting interviews and biographies to television, the press and
publishers in both America and Europe. The French television
channel TF1 will also have an exclusive interview with Lewinsky
Thursday evening with the title ``Monica Lewinsky: My Truth.''
Europeans and Americans are provided with different products by
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations special commission on human rights in
Geneva has recommended the trial of former Khmer Rouge leaders by
the International Tribunal for ``crimes against humanity.'' But in
Cambodia, people are more concerned about food than revenge. In
Phnom Penh, the government is more and more inclined toward an
amnesty, but the call for the prevention of a return of terror
like that of the Khmer Rouge era is on the rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
