<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Governing Body Meets to Determine Priorities in New Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The policymakers of the
International Labor Organization (ILO) met here Thursday to
discuss plans to sharpen the strategic focus of the organization's
activities in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The plans are at the heart of a program and budget proposal
presented by the new ILO Director-General, Juan Somavia, who
officially took office on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 481-million-dollar biennial budget proposal for 2000-2001
set out four strategic objectives for ILO at the turn of the next
century.
</P>
<P>
They include the promotion and realization of fundamental
principles and rights at work; the creation of greater
opportunities for women and men to secure decent employment and
income; the enhancement of the coverage and effectiveness of
social protection for all; and the strengthening of tripartism and
social dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other United Nations agencies, ILO has a tripartite
structure involving governments, employers and workers.
</P>
<P>
The new director-general described the budget proposal as "an
integral part of a wider process of change that will include the
establishment of clear priorities, reallocation of resources and
adaptation of the organization's management structures and program
activities to translate these priorities into action".
</P>
<P>
A special meeting will be held here on March 19-20 to discuss
the situation in Asia in detail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
