<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: U.S. Not Decided on WTO Chief Candidate Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Thursday eased Thailand's concern about the
U.S. stand on Thailand's bid for the World Trade Organization
(WTO) top post.
</P>
<P>
The United States has not "publicly" announced its endorsement
for any of the four candidates for the post, Albright told a joint
press conference with Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is seeking U.S. support for its Deputy Prime Minister
and Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, one of the four
candidates vying for the WTO top post.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Supachai was facing obstacles because the
United States snubbed his bid. U.S. officials traveling with
Albright to Thailand said Supachai is not Washington's first
choice for the job.
</P>
<P>
"We've indicated a preference for Canadian Roy Maclaren and New
Zealand's Mike Moore based on the fact that their policy views and
their vision of the WTO are more 'compatible' with ours," said a
senior U.S. state department official traveling with Albright.
</P>
<P>
"We have told the Thais we have very high regards for Supachai,
but it's a question of policy," he said as Albright arrived in
Thailand on Wednesday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Asked by Surin at the press conference to clarify the U.S.
stand, Albright said, "We have not publicly endorsed any candidate
and have not ruled out any of the four candidates." The fourth
candidate is Moroccan former trade minister Hassan Abouyoub.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand and the United States agree on the importance of the
WTO and the need for a strong leadership in world trade system.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and Thailand also agree that the WTO should
choose a new director-general as soon as possible," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the United States wants to choose a candidate who has
"the policy position and vision for the WTO that could most
closely correspond to our own."
</P>
<P>
Members of the largest world trade body have been busy choosing
a new director-general to replace Italy's Renato Ruggiero, whose
term expires at the end of April. Supachai is reportedly the
front-runner but the decision has been delayed by lack of
consensus.
</P>
<P>
Consultations among WTO members have been going on for months
and the members are to establish which candidate can be appointed
by consensus. Only if that cannot be established could a formal
vote be held.
</P>
<P>
But diplomats and trade officials say they would prefer
avoiding such an outcome, arguing that the WTO director-general
has to be the "candidate of all the members" and not a figure
whose appointment is opposed by anyone.
</P>
<P>
The world trade body chief will have to steer the organization
to the expected launch in December of fresh global trade
organizations, and to last until 2003.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the WTO and its predecessor, the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade, have been headed by a European, and
developing countries have been increasingly vocal in calling for
appointment of a figure from their midst.
</P>
<P>
Supachai has promised to bridge the gap between developing
economies and richer nations if he wins the position.
</P>
<P>
Supachai has already won backing from Japan and other Asian
countries and has earned international respect for his role in
ensuring that Thailand resisted pressure to put up trade barriers
in reaction to the financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
