<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Down in Lacklustre Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
finished slightly down in lacklustre trade Thursday, with
afternoon bargain hunters helping to lift the market from its
earlier lows, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 4.6 points down at
2,885.3, recovering from a 17.5-point deficit at one stage.
</P>
<P>
"It was a reasonably lacklustre day," said Reynold's &AMP; Co's
Peter Struk.
</P>
<P>
"A few bargain hunters came into the market this afternoon and
to finish only 4.6 points down wasn't too bad."
</P>
<P>
He said the local market was taking a wait-and-see approach
ahead of the release of data in the U.S. Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
"We may see the U.S. market get kicked up a bit tonight," Struk
said.
</P>
<P>
Struk said the Australian market followed the broad direction
of the Dow Jones Industrial Average index but received no
directional cues from Asian markets Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all industrials index shed
7.1 points to 5,232.3, while the all resources index eased 2.9 to
953.1 points.
</P>
<P>
The bank index retreated 7.0 points to 6,685.2, with ANZ the
only "Big 4" player going against trend, adding 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank slipped 18 cents, Westpac sagged five
cents and National Australia Bank eased 3.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the industrial sector, James Hardie fell 30 cents
before a trading halt was called pending an announcement from the
company.
</P>
<P>
Travel agency group Flight Center was propelled 49 cents higher
after posting a 41-percent boost in first half year net profit.
</P>
<P>
Among the telcos, Telstra lifted one cent, Cable &AMP; Wireless
Optus gained six cents and AAP fell 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
Resource major BHP slipped 6.8 cents, Rio Tinto eased 1.5
cents, and WMC added eight cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index climbed 6.6 points to 988.8, the spot price of
gold bullion in Sydney was 286.75 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared
with a close of 286.80 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 363.93 million shares traded for 924.83
million Australian dollars (573.39 million U.S. dollars). Falling
stocks outnumbered rising stocks 676 to 454, while 423 stocks
remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
