<HEADLINE> Government Policy on Minorities' Education Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- In recent years, governments at
all levels have attached unprecedentedly great importance to and
given the strongest-ever support to education for the people of
ethnic minorities, said Ma Guochang, a deputy to the National
People's Congress and headmaster of the Hui People Middle School
in Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Ma's view is shared by many other deputies who are here to
attend the upcoming Second Session of the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
The Hui People Middle School recruits over 1,200 students from
several ethnic groups including Hui, Dongxiang, Tibetan and
Mongolian. Over the past few years, the city government has
allocated special funds to help the school build a number of new
facilities and purchase advanced equipment.
</P>
<P>
"With these new facilities and equipment, I would feel guilty
if the quality of teaching cannot reach required standards," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jin Zhuhua, an ethnic Korean NPC deputy from Liaoning Province
in the northeast, is the principal of the Central Primary School
for Korean People in Lishizhai Zhai Town. She told Xinhua that her
school has been equipped with modern facilities including
computers and many other pieces of hi-tech teaching equipment.
</P>
<P>
"We want our students to be capable of competing in the 21st
century," the 31-year old woman said. Lishizhai Town is densely
populated by ethnic Koreans, a minority group in China that has
paid greater attention to education.
</P>
<P>
China has 55 minority groups, whose combined population
accounts for about eight percent of the country's total. The
Chinese government has made strenuous efforts to develop local
economy in areas inhabited by ethnic minorities through
invigorating education there.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zhirong, an NPC deputy from the southernmost province of
Hainan, is a first- generation university student of the Li ethnic
group and now a leading government official in his hometown, the
Baisha Li Autonomous County.
</P>
<P>
Chen's forefathers had to memorize things by making knots on a
string. "Ethnic minority people must rely on education to bring up
their new generation," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, currently, there are more
than 15 million students and over 700,000 teachers of ethnic
minority origin in different schools throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
During the period of 1998-2000, the government plans to invest
more than five billion yuan in building or rebuilding more than 10,
000 middle and primary schools in provinces and autonomous
regions inhabited mainly by ethnic minority people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
