<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Prices Likely to Be Static </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco prices for 1999
are likely to remain at the 1998 levels of 1.72 U.S. dollars per
kilogram when the auction floors open on April 21, said Tobacco
Trade Association President Jim Van Heerden.
</P>
<P>
Heerden told this season.
</P>
<P>
He said the prices are likely to be determined by the Malawi
tobacco auction floors which will be opening earlier than
Zimbabwe's auction floors.
</P>
<P>
The demand for burley tobacco is likely to rise as the
commodity is popular in America, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is a main tobacco trade market in the world. Tobacco
is also the country's biggest foreign currency earner. Total
earnings from tobacco exports this year is forecast at 8.5
billion Zimbabwean dollars (223 million U. S. dollars), 10 percent
less than 9.5 billion Zimbabwean dollars realized last year.
</P>
