<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Y2k Awareness, Strategy Urged for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Experts attending the Second Global
Year 2000 (Y2K) Summit, which concluded here Wednesday, called on
developing countries to raise awareness and work out plans against
the millennium bug of computer systems.
</P>
<P>
With the Y2K problem impending, the experts at the summit said
high-quality public information is one of the most powerful tools
in the fight against the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The millennium bug is a built-in flaw in older computer systems
that uses two digits to mark dates, causing them to recognize
January 1, 2000 as January 1, 1900.
</P>
<P>
A total of 40 percent of companies worldwide will experience a
critical information technology failure due to the Y2K computer
problem, they said.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank report showed that many developing countries are
unprepared for the impact of the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
In a recent World Bank survey of the Y2K preparedness in 139
developing countries, only 54 had initiated national Y2K policies,
21 were taking concrete remedial steps to safeguard their
computing systems and 33 reported high-to-medium awareness.
</P>
<P>
The majority of developing countries, even the poorest, have
computerized essential services such as power generation,
telecommunications, food and fuel distribution and the provision
of medical care, it added.
</P>
<P>
Cases in developed countries have already shown the
significance of sharing information on the Y2K problem among the
public and businesses, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
John Koskinen, chairman of the U.S. President's Council on Year
2000 Conversion, said that before the sharing of information was
increased in the United States, about one-third of small
businesses around the country had no plans to take action.
</P>
<P>
"People with access to such information will know how the
problem-solving is progressing as they move in the same process,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
If the Y2K problem in the developing countries remains unsolved
on January 1, 2000, contingency plans must be prepared, the
experts said.
</P>
<P>
The countries could create a governmental Y2K coordinating body

that issues advice and directives, and receives reports of
compliance
from government agencies and private sectors, they said.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that the developing countries divide up their
economies into such different sectors as finance, energy,
telecommunications, transportation, and medical care, and then
assign
small teams to work with these sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Y2k Awareness, Strategy Urged for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
...these sectors.
</P>
<P>
Some of the experts briefed at the meeting about their
countries' efforts against the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
Japan formed an advisory board consisting of representatives
from government ministries and major industries as a Y2K organ
under the prime minister, said Masanori Yoshikai, a Japanese
expert.
</P>
<P>
An action plan was adopted in Japan in September, 1998,
requesting related agencies to survey and announce the Y2K
progress of the government systems and critical sectors, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Amable Aguiluz, chairman of the Presidential Commission on Y2K
Compliance of the Philippines, said the Philippine government
would draw up a national contingency plan in a few months to
provide foolproof safety measures against the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
His commission will require government agencies this month to
submit their contingency plans so it can formulate a master plan
to fortify the country's defense against the millennium bug, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, many experts believe that efficient global
cooperation is another critical factor in the assurance of
successful response to the potential consequences of the Y2K.
</P>
<P>
"While wealthy countries and large companies have the money and
skilled technicians needed to immunize computers and their
operating software from the millennium bug, many of our developing
country clients cannot muster the resources to tackle a problem,"
the World Bank report said.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the summit, Y2K regional Asian
coordinators said in a declaration that they would work together
and intensify their efforts in the sharing of information across
borders and minimizing adverse Y2K effects.
</P>
<P>
They called on the World Bank, the Asian Development Bank and
other financial and multi-lateral organizations to review and
increase their level of support for national and regional Y2K
efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the inter-connected nature of systems, regional
cooperation across borders and the participation of international
sector organizations is essential to assure the continued
functioning of critical sectors," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
