<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Regulations To Get More Multinationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's capital Beijing announced
today that it has new regulations to attract more multinationals
to set up headquarters in the city.
</P>
<P>
They give companies 3 percent exemptions from local income tax
and preferential treatment in exports, equipment imports, transfer
of foreign currencies, and setting up their own finance companies.
</P>
<P>
They can also set up bonded warehouses or factories and will be
encouraged to establish investment companies which will have fewer
limitations. Regional headquarters will be given preferential
treatment in land acquisition for construction if they set up
their own research and development, training, and technical
facilities in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Regional headquarters will also be allowed to set up marketing
companies to sell goods when they are licensed by industrial and
commercial administrative departments.
</P>
<P>
Public security departments will also facilitate the exit and
entry of regional headquarters employees and their business will
be given priority in water, power, gas, heating, and
telecommunications and they will be charged at the same rate as
Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government recently announced that it will permit
overseas investors to purchase or merge with poorly-performing
Chinese enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 300 of the world's top 500 multinationals have
investment in China, over half of that in Beijing. More than 80
multinationals have moved their regional Asia headquarters here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
