<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke030427-Vietnam Takes Measures to Strengthen State Corporations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has decided to take measures
to build state corporations into strong business groups to serve
as the backbone of the national economy, official media reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has 91 state corporations, including 74 set up under
the Prime Minister's decision 90 in 1994 and controlled by
ministries and people's committees of centrally-run cities and
provinces, and 17 set up under the Prime Minister's decision 91
the same year and controlled by the government.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, they owned more than two thirds of the combined
capital and produced more than half of the total turnover of all
state-owned enterprises in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam news agency said the new measures were adopted at a
two-day conference of senior business officials of state
corporations that ended Tuesday in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
The government will strengthen the existing 17 state
corporations under the direct control of the government, with
priority given to a number of corporations having great capital,
advanced technology and important position in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The government is to accelerate the re-structuring and
equalization of the corporations' subsidiary businesses.
</P>
<P>
It will also seek uniform solutions to remove obstacles in the
legal environment, mechanism and policy to facilitate the
corporations' development.
</P>
<P>
Ministries will stop the interference into business activities
of state corporations and their subsidiaries, while strengthening
state management on them.
</P>
<P>
Party building work in state corporations was also stressed at
the conference, which was chaired by Prime Minister Phan Van Khai
and Deputy Prime Minister Ngo Xuan Loc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Strengthen Ties with Albania: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
has stressed that Turkey will further strengthen its ties with
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Demirel made the remarks in a statement issued late Wednesday
night after his meeting with visiting Albanian Prime Minister
Pandeli Majko.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said Turkey has decided to attach great importance to
peace in Albania and to continue all kinds of support for the
development of democracy and economy in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Demirel expressed great concern over the situation in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, saying that as a member of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Turkey will attend the
measures to be taken by the NATO.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo have been on rise since February 1998 when
bloody clashes erupted between Serbian police and ethnic Albanians
who demand independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened military intervention if the two warring
sides fail to reach a ceasefire soon.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Majko, who arrived here Wednesday on a two-day
visit, said that Albania is also keen on further developing
Albanian-Turkish relations in every field.
</P>
<P>
Terming his talks with Majko as "very productive," Turkish
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said Wednesday Turkey and Albania
will step up cooperation in the defense industry and economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
