<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Passes New Constitution to Create Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's National Assembly
ended its three-day special session and passed a constitutional
amendment Thursday, paving the way for the creation of a
controversial and long-awaited senate.
</P>
<P>
Assembly President Prince Norodom Ranariddh presided over the
session attended by more than 100 out of 122 parliamentarians. Sam
Rainsy, president of his self-named opposition party, was not
present.
</P>
<P>
The process of amending nearly all the chapters of the
Constitution in order to create a senate was over smoothly. Prime
Minister Hun Sen and Prince Ranariddh both expressed satisfaction
with the proceedings, saying they were carried out "in a good
atmosphere and in a democratic way."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said he expected the senate would be formed next week.
</P>
<P>
After the amending, the new constitution is expanded to include
158 articles while the old one, adopted in 1993, had 139 articles.
</P>
<P>
Under the amended constitution, the senate will comprise half
of the members in the National Assembly, that means there will be
61 senators.
</P>
<P>
Under a proportionate system of representation, the Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) will have 31 senators, FUNCINPEC party 21 and
the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) 7. The remaining two will be appointed
by the King.
</P>
<P>
CPP President Chea Sim will be the president of the Senate and
will take the role of acting head of state during the absence or
illness of the King.
</P>
<P>
The senators will have parliamentary immunity and their term
will be five years. At the same time, the senate, along with the
National Assembly, has the right to initiate law and plays the
role of coordinating between the government and the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC and CPP reached an agreement on creating a senate in
November last year as part of a compromise to form a new coalition
government to end months of post-election deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Failure to create the senate had been cited as a reason for
Cambodia's delayed admission into the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Although the opposition SRP, which holds 15 seats in the
assembly, opposes forming a senate, saying the body is to be set
up for power-sharing between the ruling party and FUNCINPEC and
will spend money uselessly, but it made no barrier during voting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
