<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Resumes Oil Export Through Iraqi-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Thursday morning resumed
pumping oil through the Iraqi-Turkish pipeline after repairing a
communications repeater station damaged by U.S. and British
warplanes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi-Turkish pipeline, which runs from the northern Iraqi
field of Kirkul to the port of Ceyhan in south Turkey, was cut in
the raid and oil transfer halted, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline carries half the oil Iraq is allowed to export
under the United Nations-Iraqi oil-for-food program which allows
Iraq to use its oil revenues to pay for food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones in Iraq
have intensified their bombardments on Iraqi targets recently.
</P>
<P>
United States Defense Secretary William Cohen said on Monday
that attacks would continue on a widening range of Iraqi air
defense targets in the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed by the U.S.-led western allies
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression." 
</P>
</TEXT>
