<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Stable Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Shilling was stable
against the U.S. dollar in quite trading Wednesday at the Nairobi
Exchange Market, supported by dollar inflows from the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Four banks including the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) posted the
shilling at an opening means rate between 63.45 shillings and
63.70 shillings against the dollar, little changed from Tuesday's
closing rate between 63. 40 shillings and 63.75 shillings.
</P>
<P>
The CBK Wednesday posted the shillings at an opening mean
indicative rate of 63.58 shillings to the dollar compared to 63.63
shillings at Tuesday's open, the East African Standard newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The shilling was lower against the pound and the euro with the
CBK quoting it at 102.66 shillings and 69.41 shillings
respectively, from 102. 43 shillings and 69.72 shillings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers at the market said that there were improved dollar
inflows from the tea and coffee sectors and the inflows were
mainly taken up by importers, adding that dollar demand was
fairly subdued.
</P>
<P>
Local financial analysts held that the shilling is likely to
hold stable around 63 shillings and was unlikely to return to the
61 shillings level before the cabinet reshuffle in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
The shilling dropped just after two hours when former Finance
Minister Simeon Nyachae resigned from the government in the
cabinet reshuffle ordered by President Daniel arap Moi on
February 18.  
</P>
</TEXT>
