<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imelda to Be Back in Court for 5 Graft Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Imelda Marcos will be back in court
on March 15-16 for a pre-trial hearing of five criminal cases of
graft, four of which involve her former management of four Marcos
dummy foundations.
</P>
<P>
Imelda allegedly used the four foundations to hide 590 million
U.S. dollars of her family's loot in Swiss banks from 1968 to
1971.
</P>
<P>
A local court Wednesday set the pre-trial hearing after making
public a February 23 order resurrecting the cases against the
widow of late president Ferdinand Marcos. The cases have been
dormant for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
In a third legal strike against the Marcoses this year, the
anti-graft court denied Imelda's second appeal seeking to dismiss
the graft charges against her.
</P>
<P>
Imelda allegedly committed the crimes while she was a member of
the Interim National Law Making Body from 1978 to 1984.
</P>
<P>
In a nine-page resolution, the court gave the green light for
trying Imelda for directly and indirectly managing Maler, Palmy,
Rayby and Trinidad, four of the 12 Swiss foundations which
controlled the family's Swiss accounts.
</P>
<P>
The 590 million dollars are now held in escrow at the
Philippine National Bank.
</P>
<P>
The fifth graft case arose from her "securing and heavily
recommending" an approval by the then central bank governor for a
25-million-dollar loan applied in 1982 by Asian Reliability Corp,
owned by a Marcos crony.
</P>
<P>
All the five cases were filed on December 16, 1991 by Ombudsman
Vasquez with the court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
