<HEADLINE> hke030425 - Albright Reaffirms Security Partnership with Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here Thursday that her country will build
a stronger partnership with Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Albright told a joint press conference with Thai Foreign
Minister Surin Pitsuwan that friendship between the United States
and Thailand "is firm" and "I am confident we will build an even
stronger partnership in the future."
</P>
<P>
She said she visited Thailand to "reaffirm America's deep
friendship with our long-time ally Thailand and our strong support
for its political and economic reform initiatives." Albright
arrived in Thailand on Wednesday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
She urged Thailand to spur recovery through overhaul of
economic legal framework and bank recapitalization and
restructuring of corporate debts.
</P>
<P>
She said, "although there remains a great deal of work to be
done in these areas, Thailand is increasingly serving as a model
for others in this region."
</P>
<P>
She said her country was working bilaterally with many partners
in this region to address the problems caused by the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The United States, she said, "is prepared to work with Thailand
towards the purchase and use of U.S.-made S16 fighter aircraft.
This will enforce our strong bilateral security relationship."
</P>
<P>
Surin said Thailand and the United States will cooperate in
various fields, including the fight against drugs and
mine-clearing operations.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S.-funded law-enforcement school in Thailand
would help boost the fight against international crimes,
particularly drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The school is slated to take in the first class of students
from members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
and China next week.
</P>
<P>
Albright said: "We respect this joint Thai-U.S. institution to
help bolster cooperation throughout the region in the fight
against trans-national crime."
</P>
<P>
Surin disclosed that the United States would provide Thailand
with 3 million dollars in a two-year program to remove the mines
along Thailand's border with Cambodia. There are reportedly
700,000 land mines along the Thai-Cambodian border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
