<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Voices Concern Over Iraqi Air Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua)-- Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao today voiced China's deep concern over the recent air
strike against Iraq by the U.S. and Britain, which resulted in the
damage of oil pipeline installations and the death of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of "no-flying zone" in Iraq runs counter to
the UN Charter and international norms, Zhu said when asked about
China's response to the latest air raid at today's routine press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Military actions taken by the U.S. and Britain would only
escalate the tension instead of helping break the stalemate, the
spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated China's stance, saying that the national
sovereignty, territorial integrity, and independence of Iraq
should be fully respected, and that the Iraqi issue should be
settled through peaceful means based on relevant UN resolutions
and international norms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
