<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Benefit from "100 Lamps" Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Colin Mackeras, a scholar from
Australia on his third visit to Tibet, is surprised that women no
longer carry water in buckets from the outskirts of Xigaze city.
</P>
<P>
But thanks to a recently completed 45 million yuan water
project, financed by China's leading economic powerhouse Shanghai,
gone are the days when the city's 80,000 people were forced to
drink water from rivers, ponds and even ditches.
</P>
<P>
Mackeras, Director of the Institute of the Asian Culture
Studies of the Australian Griffith University, said that each time
he came to Tibet he could see the great changes that have taken
place.
</P>
<P>
The water project in Xigaze is just one of the 62 projects
being carried out with aid from 31 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions in China, in line with the decision of a
central government work conference on Tibet in 1994.
</P>
<P>
By 1985, 43 earlier projects had already been completed with
support of other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Now the total of 105 projects, known as "100 lamps" among
Tibetan people, span energy, transportation, telecommunications,
industry, agriculture, animal husbandry, forestry, water
conservancy, education, culture and medicine, as well as
broadcasting, television and urban construction.
</P>
<P>
The central government has planned to invest some 2.3 billion
yuan on the latest 62 projects. So far, 4 billion yuan in total
from all sources has been injected. Now most of the projects have
been completed and are operational apart from the Manla Water
Conservancy Project and the Woka Power Station.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi Norbu, a herdsman from Xanza County in northern Tibet,
just bought a 29 inch color TV before the Tibetan Lunar New Year,
which also falls on mid February this year.
</P>
<P>
His long-cherished dream of watching TV is finally realized due
to the operation of the Jiagang Power Station in the county, which
is 4,600 meters above the sea level. The power station was built
with the help of east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million people in the southwestern Tibetan
Autonomous Region have benefited from the "100 lamps" project
built over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
In Lhasa, the capital of the autonomous region, urbanites now
can watch 35 satellite TV programs every day.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth rate of the region, which ranked low before the
construction of the projects, increased to 17 percent in 1995 and
has kept growing at above 10 percent for five successive years,
exceeding the national average growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the "bottlenecks" that restricted local development have
been done away with. The region's installed generating capacity
rose to 3.1 billion kilowatts with the operation of the region's
largest power station Yamzho Yumco last year and a group of power
stations at the county level, doubling that of five years ago.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the projects, Tibet now takes on a new
image. Highways stretching 22,000 km link all counties in Tibet
except Medo. So far, 25 out of 100 people in the autonomous
regional capital have telephones and all 71 counties in Tibet have
access to telephones, realizing the goal set for the year 2000
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 366 additional medical institutions have been set up
throughout the region since 1985, improving the health of local
Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the 105 projects have greatly
improved Tibet's infrastructure facilities and investment
environment.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regional government also adjusted the industrial
structure over the past few years and listed forestry, mining,
building materials, tourism, the processing of farm and animal
husbandry products and local handicrafts industry as the region's
five pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the autonomous region Legqog said: "The
projects built with the aid of the whole country epitomize the
warmth of the big family of the motherland."
</P>
<P>
"By the end of the century," he added,"Tibet aims to achieve
self-sufficiency in the supply of food grain, edible oil and meat
and basically become better off." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
