<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Addresses Forestry Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China is preparing to introduce
strong measures to protect forestry resources and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhibao, director of the State Forestry Administration,
said Wednesday that China will place increased emphasis on
protecting and developing forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
Plans of the State Council for 1999 call for initiating a
natural forest conservation project and a number of major forestry
projects on ecosystem protection.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed to the wide gap between the performance of
forestry police agencies and the increasing demands for protecting
the resources.
</P>
<P>
He said that strong measures will be taken to crack down on
illegal logging, poaching of wildlife and illegal occupation of
forests.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the country's forest police agencies have
handled 1.36 million forestry and wildlife cases since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the administration instructed related
departments at all levels to strictly limit approvals of
construction projects which encroach on forest areas and firmly
curb illegal reclamation.
</P>
<P>
Stipulations and regulations governing implementation of the
Forestry Law require provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities to submit applications and related documents to the
State Council prior to approving related construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The administration is responsible for approving projects
involving tracts of land covering less than 70 hectares and is
required to submit relevant documents involving larger tracts to
the State Council for final approval.
</P>
<P>
A recent investigation revealed that 830 land development
projects in 98 cities and counties involved the illegal occupation
of forest land.
</P>
<P>
The investigation also revealed that various local officials
exceeded their authority by approving 90-odd projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
