<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flawless Diamond Discovered in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists have discovered
a flawless diamond using their new geo-prospecting theory in
Longyou of east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Such diamonds are one of the ten most rarely seen minerals in
China and it is the first time that one like this has been
discovered in the Zhejiang region.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from Nanjing Geological and Mineral Research
Institute claim that using the new techniques they have also found
clues which could lead to diamonds being discovered in southern
China.
</P>
<P>
A test made by a state lab - the Structural Research Center of
the Chinese University of Science and Technology - indicated that
the recently found diamond is of high grade purity.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists declined to reveal either its size or
weight.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent tests on nearby minerals found alongside the diamond
indicted that it was formed 400 kilometers deep under the earth's
crust.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Nanjing Geological and Mineral Research
Institute Attached to the Ministry of Land and Resources said
their investigations showed that diamonds are usually formed about
400 kilometers underground, with temperatures around 1,800 degrees
centigrade and with a 135,000 barometric pressure.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they said, the diamond is only brought to the
surface layers under certain conditions where it is between two
rock plates which force it up as though in a volcanic eruption. As
such "eruption" opportunities are rare, diamonds are thus very
precious and valuable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
