<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Call For Protection of River Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the Second Session of
the National People's Congress (NPC) from northwest China's
Qinghai Province seem determined to cash in on the upcoming NPC
session to amplify their appeal for protecting ecological
environment of the sources of Yangtze and Yellow rivers, the
nation's first and second longest rivers.
</P>
<P>
They are to submit a suggestion to the NPC annual session
scheduled to convene on March 5-15, according to Bai Enpei,
governor of Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
"The Yangtze and Yellow rivers originate from Qinghai and run
across most parts of the country. Therefore protection of the two
major rivers need concerted efforts of the whole country," Bai
said.
</P>
<P>
To protect and improve ecology in the sources areas of the
rivers, the local and central governments have carried out a
series of afforestation projects which have seen millions of trees
planted in the areas to reduce soil erosion and halt the spread of
desertification, Bai said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, six counties on the upper reaches of the
Yellow River are designated as the key areas for ecological
improvement and the first stage of the project to improve ecology
around Qinghai Lake is proceeding smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Despite the protection measures and initial success, forests
and vegetation in the river source areas have fast disappearing in
the past years. Excessive use of pastures for animal husbandry,
increasing assaults of sand and desertification have pushed up the
snow line, which results in drastic drop of water on the upper
reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
"The situation could go worse if we don't take prompt actions,"
said La Bingli, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
Qinghai Provincial People's Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
