<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former National Center Shan Kicks Cameraman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Chinese national center
Shan Tao kicked a cameraman here on Wendesday during a Chinese
first division basketball match when his Beijing Ducks club lost
to Beijing Aoshen 96-104.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Shan kicked down Jiang Li, a cameraman from
Beijing Television, in a row during a timeout in the first quarter,
the local newspaper Sports Express said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The brawl errupted when Shan pushed Jiang aside when
approaching the bench from the court which offended Jiang that had
a camera on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
The Sports Express said that Shan turned back and kicked Jiang
down after he expressed anger towards the 2.15-meter giant.
</P>
<P>
"I was very anxious to listen to the instruction of the coach,
but this man was right in the way. You know this match was very
important to us," Shan was quoted by the China Sports Daily as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"I know I was wrong. I will accept any punishment by the
Chinese Basketball Association (CBA). But the cameraman was not
kicked down by me. He fell to the ground after someone else pulled
him away from me," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's colleagues submitted their protest to CBA after the
match. Xin Lancheng, a top official of CBA, told reporters that
CBA will make a decision on this matter after studying the report
from the technical representatives of the match.
</P>
<P>
The Sports Express said that the Duck Club's general manager
Sun Minzhi and head coach Sun Fengwu had apologized to Jiang by
phone last night after the match.
</P>
<P>
Shan was selected into the national squad at 19 but lost the
place in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
