<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Pacific Chief: China Threat Hyped Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) - The chief officer of the U.S.
Pacific forces said that some people in Washington are
exaggerating the threat by China's missile program, according to
the latest issue of Defense News to be published here next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Adm. Joseph Prueher, outgoing commander in chief of the U.S.
forces in the Pacific, also called for continued military-to-
military contacts between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
"We've gone from zero dialogue in 1996 to our ability to talk
to them meaningfully about a number of preventive issues," Prueher
was quoted as saying in his last official interview as head of the
100,000-strong U.S. force stationed in the Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Prueher made the statement at a time when some lobbyists in
Washington are hyping up the threat by China as a way to involve
Taiwan in the proposed Theater Missile Defense (TMD) system, a
move that has been strongly criticized by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
"There is not some incipient missile deployment in China,"
Prueher said, but he declined to give details of a secret report
drafted by the Pentagon for Congress, which focuses on China's
missile deployment that some Americans have alleged would tilt the
balance in favor of Chinese mainland against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Prueher said he is hopeful that the talks between the two sides
across the Taiwan Strait "will yield some sort of productive way
to move along together".
</P>
<P>
While urging the United States to continue its policy of
cooperative engagement with China "from a position of strength",
Prueher stressed that "what we need is more discussion."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Secretary William Cohen, in an interview in
Hawaii following the induction of Adm. Dennis Blair as the new
commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific Command, also expressed his
hope for continued engagement with China, Defense News reported.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who paid a visit to Beijing about a year ago, said that
during his upcoming trip to China, he will push forward bilateral
military ties through computerized exercises involving the two
militaries in cooperative humanitarian operations.
</P>
<P>
Senator Ted Stevens, a republican from Alaska, backed up Cohen'
s emphasis on the expansion of military-to-military links between
the United States and China, according to Defense News.
</P>
<P>
"We can't afford to get into a confrontational relationship
with China. We must recognize they are a growing power in the
region and conduct ourselves accordingly...That requires
understanding, sensitivity and reciprocity from both sides,"
Stevens was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Stevens said that he and other members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee will visit China this month with an aim of
seeking opportunities to advance bilateral relations, including
the eventual drop of sanctions against China.
</P>
<P>
The senator said that the time is not yet ripe for the lifting
of the sanctions, but, "I think it's coming." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
