<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Undertakes Rational Urban Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's urbanization strategy has
effectively controlled the number and scale of large cities and
provided greater room for the development of small to medium-sized
cities and rural towns.
</P>
<P>
Ye Rutang, vice-minister of construction, said today that China
has adopted a series of laws and regulations governing urban
development.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Construction has also issued a series of rules
and regulations related to sites for urban construction projects,
city development programs and transfers of state-owned land and
development areas to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide enforcement of the laws and regulations has
effectively promoted the development of 666 cities and greatly
improved local economic structures.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities in various areas, including cities and towns
surrounding Shanghai, the Yangtze River Valley and the Pearl River
Delta, have adopted urban development plans based on the laws.
Related efforts have in turn promoted harmonious urban and
regional development, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has also introduced a serious of rules
and regulations to protect the unique features of famous historic
and cultural cities. A list of more than 100 cities of the
category has been made public to this effect.
</P>
<P>
Ye said China's urbanization program has proceeded on a sound
basis, and projected that the country will have some 800-odd
cities by early in the 21st century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
