<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubber Market Faces Increasing Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The price for rubber price
continued to rise in January but no dramatic increases are
expected through the remainder of the year due to falling
international prices.
</P>
<P>
A recent issue of China Chemical Industry News reported that
the rubber supply dropped sharply to 100,600 tons in January due
to controls placed on production of synthetic rubber, the end of
the rubber tapping season and the anti-smuggling campaign. However,
the declining export volume and expanded scale of construction led
to a 45 percent surge in demand and rising prices for rubber.
</P>
<P>
No sharp price rises for rubber are expected due to the
oversupply on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that major rubber producers such as Thailand and
Malaysia face a sluggish market as they enter their peak
production seasons.
</P>
<P>
They also note that falling rubber prices will widen the gap
between domestic and international prices and place greater
pressure on China's rubber imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
