<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Group Says High-Level Talks Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The anti-government Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) said Thursday that a meeting between
President Joseph Estrada and MILF Chairman Hashim Salamat could
push through in the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, such initiative of confidence-building measure should
come from the government as the MILF leaders are merely
"respondents" to the proposal, MILF Vice Chairman Al Haj Murad
said in Cotabato city, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"If the government decides to push through with the meeting, we
are always ready for it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that as far as he is concerned, plans to get on with
the proposed meeting is still intact as government
representatives led by Economic Affairs Adviser Robert Aventajado
are still on constant contact with them with regard to the
matter.
</P>
<P>
"It was just temporarily called off," Murad said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada and Salamat were scheduled to meet in Cotabato city
last Saturday, but the meeting was canceled due to disputes over
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"Both the government and the MILF recognize the existence of a
'third force' out to sabotage the government-MILF peace process so
we should be very careful of this as any untoward incident
inflicted on our leaders might ignite a full-scale war in
Mindanao," Murad said.
</P>
<P>
During the past two decades, the MILF has been fighting for an
independent Islamic state, but the government has firmly rejected
the demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
