<HEADLINE> Australia's Wool Output to Drop 8 Percent: AWPEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia's wool production is
forecast to drop eight percent this year because farmers have
reduced their flocks due to the poor market.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Wool Production Forecasting Committee (AWPFC)
this week slightly revised up an original estimate of 629 million
kg of wool to 636 million kg for the 1998-1999 season with a range
between 626 million kg to 646 million kg.
</P>
<P>
But while the forecast has improved because of better weather
conditions in many wool growing areas, the overall estimate
represents a fall of three percent, or 19 million kg, on the
previous season, with production in the 1999-2000 season expected
to fall another five percent.
</P>
<P>
"Wool market conditions have been terrible and were
particularly bad last year which has seen an increasing decline in
sheep numbers," said Peter Morgan, acting chairman of AWPFC.
</P>
<P>
"Last year we had 155 million sheep, and this year we are
expecting 147 million sheep and lambs to be shorn but the lower
numbers have been partly offset by better seasonal conditions
which have led to an increase in fleece weight."
</P>
<P>
The AWPFC estimates 147.1 million sheep will be shorn with an
average cut of 4.32 kg per head in 1998-1999 but that only 143.6
million sheep will be shorn in 1999-2000 with an average cut of
4.21 kg/head.
</P>
<P>
The first estimate for the 1999-2000 season is 605 million kg
with a range between 585 to 625 million kg.
</P>
<P>
The anticipated fall in 1999-2000 season reflects an expected
further decrease in sheep numbers as well as increased mating to
fat lamb sires.
</P>
<P>
The AWPFC estimates also reflect a growing trend in Australia
towards finer wool production with the clip expected to show a
continuing increase in the proportion of wool measuring less than
19.6 microns in both years at the expense of broader wools.
</P>
<P>
"Most reductions in the significant falls in the sheep
populations in the 90s occurred in broader wool sheep so finer
wool sheep are now a higher proportion, but the estimates also
reflect attempts to grow finer wool," Morgan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
