<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Warns Against Fallout From Tribunal of KR Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen asked U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Wednesday to caution
to decide a tribunal of Khmer Rouge leaders, warning it could
cause panic and war if not properly conducted.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the remarks in his letter to Kofi Annan responding
to a report carried out by the New York Times which said a U.N.
panel had recommended that a new international tribunal be
convened to try about a dozen senior Khmer Rouge officials on
charges of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Hun Sen reiterated that "We have never rejected
the accountability of the Khmer Rouge leaders for the crimes of
genocide in Cambodia."
</P>
<P>
"We just want, however, to caution that any decision to bring
the Khmer Rouge leaders to justice must also take into full
account the Cambodia's need for peace, national
reconciliation...," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, if improperly and heedlessly conducted, the trials
of Khmer Rouge leaders would panic other former Khmer Rouge
officers and its rank and file, who have already surrendered, into
turning back to the jungle and renewing the guerrilla war in
Cambodia," Hun Sen pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. experts came to Cambodia last November to investigate
the Khmer Rouge issues and made the report to Kofi Annan. Now they
are awaiting for the final decision from Annan on whether Khmer
Rouge leaders be tried or not.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said: "It is quite obvious that peace and national
reconciliation are the important condition for rehabilitation,
socio-economic development and alleviation of poverty of the
Cambodian people."
</P>
<P>
"From our most bitter experience in the past, whenever a war
break out, we are not only unable to find the justice for the
people, but also unable to protect the people from death," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also said in his letter that "with this objective in
mind, we are now studying the South African case and the
experience of the South African Truth and Reconciliation
Commission in dealing with justice for the Cambodian people as
well as peace and national reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
But Prince Ranariddh, president of the National Assembly and
FUNCINPEC Party, told the reporters Thursday that in his opinion
the tribunal of Khmer Rouge leaders would not cause panic. "I
think we have to start a fair and just trial of Khmer Rouge," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition party leader Sam Ransy, meanwhile, also
expressed his support Wednesday to set up an international
tribunal of Khmer Rouge leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
