<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, March 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's Senate Wednesday approved Arminio Fraga as
the country's Cental Bank president.
</P>
<P>
After three hours of debate, 57 senators voted in favor and 20
against the appointment of the 41-year-old Fraga as the new
president of the Central Bank. Fraga, has been an associate of
billionaire financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the nomination of Fraga was no surprise and was
awaited as much by the government as by the markets. (Brazil-
Central Bank President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian President Fernando Cardoso said Wednesday
that the exchange rate between the real and the U.S. dollar will
normalize in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The president made this statement when the exchange rate
reached 2.23 reals to the dollar on Tuesday, a situation he
considers to be exaggerated. (Brazil-Exchange Rate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL-- South Korean banks' non-performing loans amounted to 22.
22 trillion won (18.15 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of 1998,
accounting for 7.4 percent of their total lending, the Financial
Supervisory Service (FSS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 4.3 percent rise from 21.31 trillion
won (17.41 billion dollars) recorded in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Domestic banks' non-performing loans totaled 12.23 trillion won
(9.99 billion dollars) in 1996, then surged to 28.04 trillion won
(22.91 billion dollars) and fell to 22.42 trillion won (18.32
billion dollars) last September. (SKorea-Loans)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government assured the public
Wednesday that there is no threat of capital flight by major
multinational corporations from the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Jose Pardo of the Department of Trade and Industry (
DTI) said in a radio interview this morning that a talk with
officials of these companies showed that reports of a planned
pullout were "exaggerated." (Philippines-Capital Flight)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Hong Kong's Financial Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-
kuen began to present to the Legislative Council the 1999-2000
Budget here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Tsang is expected to spend two hours on delivering the 49-page
budget, which he admitted was "the hardest Budget" he had ever
drawn up. (Hong Kong-Budget) 
</P>
