<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka At Odds With India Over Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's business community has
expressed displeasure at the turn of events in the implementation
of the India-Sri Lanka Free Trade Agreement, business sources said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The whole purpose and concept of this free trade agreement
have been lost," said Nimal Samarakkody, chairman of the Ceylon
National Chamber of Industries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed last December when President Chandrika
Kumaratunga visited India, holds a deadline of March 1 for
finalizing the negative list of goods for which concessionary
tariffs will not be granted in line with the trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that India has included tea, rubber, coconuts
and garments in its negative list, which will be a big blow to Sri
Lankan exports as these four sectors are areas where Sri Lanka
holds a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
The trade agreement has become a one-sided affair benefiting
only India, Samarakkody said.
</P>
<P>
Rohan Perera, chairman of the Foundation of Small and Medium
Industries, said the agreement should have been compiled in
consultation with the trade chambers.
</P>
<P>
"We are not on equal terms with India. India's negative list is
unfavorable," he added.
</P>
<P>
As trouble grew in Sri Lanka over the agreement there were
official attempts at the diplomatic level to salvage it. Officials
are hopeful that they could sort out matters in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, they insisted that India including tea and rubber in
their negative list was unacceptable to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
A private sector official said, "The Indians have very clearly
displayed bad faith. This has led to the virtual collapse of the
treaty." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Provide Loan for Bangladesh's Power Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) --The World Bank (WB) has proposed a
600-million-U.S.-dollar loan for Bangladesh's power sector reform,
press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The offer was made on Wednesday, ending a nine-year suspension
slapped after the country's power authorities failed to cut down
high system loss that once was as high as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that only 15 percent people of Bangladesh are now
getting power... we have taken steps to generate more electricity
to cover more areas and meet growing demand for our
industrialization process," Commerce and Industries Minister
Tofail Ahmed told a visiting WB power delegation.
</P>
<P>
The government is implementing a project at the cost of 1,050
million taka (21.65 million U.S. dollars) for the rural
electrification in eight districts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has privatized the energy sector and "we want to
involve the private sector in the distribution system in addition
to generation of electricity," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The installed capacity of power generation in Bangladesh is
3,091 megawatt, but the available power generation capacity is
only 1,900-2,000 megawatt against a peak hour requirement of 2,300
megawatt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
