<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Suffers Turbulence in Foreign Exchange Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's foreign exchange market
has experienced continuing turbulence recently with the local
currency, the sucre, reaching exchange rates as high as 12,500 to
one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's record high exchange rate, rising by 25 percentage
points from Tuesday's 10,000 sucre to the dollar, has resulted in
an increase in major exchange rate points in all currencies
throughout the country, which have also been out of control for
some time.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the turbulence to Ecuador's unstable
political situation, a weak economy, poor revenues, tight taxes, a
discredited local currency, and the outflow of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
Since the devaluation of the sucre by the government last
September, Ecuador has experienced panic buying of the green back.
</P>
<P>
In January, a one-percent tax on bank transactions was imposed,
which caused further turbulence in the exchange market and
encouraged an excessive amount of foreign capital to leave the
country. The exodus of foreign capital was estimated at more than
one billion dollars in the past two months, said press reports.
</P>
<P>
Since the central bank allowed the sucre to float freely in
February, the dollar has continued to climb and has created chaos
in the market. The sucre has lost over 140 percent of its value in
the 5.5 months since last September, the statistics confirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
