<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Keen to Increase Exports to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A Thai trade delegation has showed
keen interest in expanding trade by exporting more to Bangladesh,
an English-language newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to boost our exports here. Our main objective is to
increase Thai exports to South Asian countries including
Bangladesh," said Pisit Kijviriya, leader of the delegation, at a
meeting with local business leaders on Wednesday, The Daily Star
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member Thai mission, which earlier visited India and
Nepal, arrived in Dhaka Tuesday on a two-day business tour, which
is part of their 10-day South Asian trip.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between the two countries is not yet
significant although they have been enjoying good trade relations
for long, said M.A. Mumin, vice president of the Federation of
Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FBCCI).
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year, Bangladesh imported goods worth
107.03 million U.S. dollars from Thailand and exported 16.51
million dollars of goods to the Southeast Asian nation, suffering
a trade deficit of 90.52 million dollars, according to Mumin.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi business leaders called upon the Thai entrepreneurs
to invest in joint-venture projects in the country to improve the
buying capacity of people.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Thai investment here could help increase
Bangladesh's exports to other countries," Mumin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai Ambassador to Bangladesh Pithaya Pookaman said
that the embassy would issue multiple visas to Bangladeshi
businessmen to help promote bilateral trade between the two
countries, at the request of the FBCCI for relaxing visa
formalities for Bangladeshi businessmen and for introducing
multiple visas with one or two years' validity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
