<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dell Opens Online Superstore To Sell Computer-related Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Dell Computer Corp. Wednesday
said it plans to introduce an online superstore for consumers to
buy computer-related products.
</P>
<P>
The store will initially offer more than 30,000 computer-
related products from many leading brand manufacturer's, including
printers, digital cameras, scanners, games, software and business
products, according to a report from the company.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other online stores, which force buyers to consider only
selected goods -- making it difficult to comparison-shop -- Dell
promised to allow shoppers to search for products by category,
manufacturer, product model, features and price. It also promised
to offer extremely competitive pricing on popular products.
</P>
<P>
Dell is the world's top direct seller of personal computers and
currently sells more than 14 million U.S. dollars in computers
each day over the Web, 25 percent of the company's business.
</P>
<P>
Dell's online superstore will "offer online shoppers a
convenient way to buy the software and accessories they need for
their computers," said Michael Dell, chairman and chief executive
officer of the company.
</P>
<P>
The Internet superstore is part of Dell's commitment to
generate 50 percent of revenues through the Internet within one
and one-half years.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts see a shift in the personal computer business
to sales of consumer electronics and other low-cost commodity
goods instead of high-powered, costly PCs. Online hardware sales
are expected to rise to 15 billion dollars in 2003 from one
billion dollars in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
