<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Petrochemical Export Down China Witnesses Declining Petrochemical Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua)-- China's 1998 import and export of
petrochemicals fell 8.05 percent to 55.17 billion U.S. dollars due
to the adverse impact of the financial crisis engulfing Asia.
</P>
<P>
The petrochemical sector imported products valued at 32.57
billion dollars, down 8.86 percent on 1997, with exports falling 6.
8 percent to 22.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in the import of crude oil and oil products was
part of the factor for the declining trade of the sector,
according to trade officials.
</P>
<P>
Last year, crude oil and oil products import amounted to 53.23
million tons, down by 9.13 million tons or 14.6 percent from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Automobile tires, pesticides and caustic soda ranked as the
sector's leading export items.
</P>
<P>
Exports of automobile tires surged 79.32 percent to 13.43
million sets, with pesticide exports rising 21.9 percent to 106,
900 tons and caustic soda growing 14.16 percent to 262,100 tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
