<HEADLINE> Myanmar Attends Regional Environment Symposium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is sending a judicial
delegation, led by Chief Justice U Aung Toe, to attend a Southeast
Asian regional symposium on judiciary and law concerning
environment conservation to be held in Manila, the Philippines,
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The symposium will last until this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar delegation includes a supreme court justice, two
officials of the National Commission for Environmental Affairs
(NCEA) and the Attorney-General's Office.
</P>
<P>
In July last year, Myanmar participated in the Environment
Ministers Meeting of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, during which it coordinated
with other ASEAN members measures to deal with recurrence of
forest fires and haze in the region under a regional haze action
plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Myanmar NCEA has since last October been seeking
ideas and recommendations for a national framework environmental
legislation and an environmental impact assessment legislation.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar adopted a national environment policy in late 1994 with
the aim of achieving harmony and balance between the environment
and development through integrating environmental consideration
into the development process.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the NCEA formulated and published Myanmar Agenda 21, a
plan of action for sustainable development in the country.
</P>
<P>
Presently, Myanmar has altogether 57 environment-related laws,
but most of which are incidental environmental laws and not
specifically intended for environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
