<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Councilor Meets Latvian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIGA, Latvia, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's State Councilor Wu Yi
met Wednesday with Latvian leaders to discuss political and
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
In her meeting with President Guntis Ulmanis, Wu said relations
between the two countries have made great progress since Ulmanis'
visit to China in 1994.
</P>
<P>
China and Latvia have signed 10 cooperation agreements and two
more will be signed during her current visit, She said.
</P>
<P>
Ulmanis said that the joint statement signed by the two
countries during his 1994 China visit is an important document
that underlines the guidelines for the development of relations.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade is growing at a fast pace, the Latvian
president said. Wu's visit will certainly help push forward the
cooperative relations in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China supports Latvia's efforts in maintaining
national independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity and
respects the choice of social system by the Latvian people.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting with Latvian Prime Minister Vilis
Kristopans, Wu said that China appreciates the "One China"
principle adopted by Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Kristopans said that China is one of the first countries that
recognized the independence of Latvia and Latvia will continue to
honor China's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Wu also exchanged views with Latvian Deputy Prime
Minister Anatoly Gorbunov on how to further economic and trade
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that bilateral trade was small although it recorded a
220 percent growth last year. She proposed to increase direct
contacts between enterprises of the two countries and enlarge the
scope of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Gorbunov agreed to Wu's proposal and said that Latvia is
willing to enhance cooperation with China in specific areas.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Wu announced China's decision to donate 3
million yuan (374,000 U.S. dollars) to Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Wu arrived here Tuesday from Tallinn, the capital of Estonia,
for a two-day visit to Latvia. She will also visit Lithuania,
Belarus and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
