<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Rejects U.S. Request for Use of Air Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Peru again rejected the United States'
request to use its air bases for anti-drug operations, according
to press reports here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
John Dickson, U.S. Information Services (USIS) chief in Peru,
said Tuesday after a teleconference that Peruvian President
Alberto Fujimori had ruled out the possibility the second time.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been planning on using Peruvian air bases
for interception of drug transport from Bolivia and Peru to
Colombia, and further to North America.
</P>
<P>
But even before traveling to the United States early February,
Fujimori made his position clear on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Search for air bases for U.S. anti-drug planes is gaining
special importance since the United States is to hand back the "
Howard" base to Panama in May.
</P>
<P>
The request to use the Peruvian air bases was made last year by
General Charles Wihelm, chief of the U.S. army's South Command.
Dickson said further talks with other countries on the topic will
take place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
