<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Government Debt Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' foreign debt
increased to nearly 17.5 billion U.S. dollars in January, from
16.5 billion dollars at the end of 1998, as the National
Government started borrowing abroad early this year to fund its
pump-priming activities.
</P>
<P>
Data released Wednesday by the Bureau of Treasury showed that
the increase in foreign debts pushed the government's total
obligations to 1.538 trillion pesos (38.45 billion dollars) at the
end of January from 1.496 trillion pesos (37.4 billion dollars)
last December.
</P>
<P>
A government source said the increase in foreign debt was due
to the one billion dollars the National Government raised through
a global bond floating, and analysts expected this trend to
continue for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the global bonds, the government is also
planning to float 340 million dollars in Eurobonds this month, and
is eyeing a 500-million floating of 30-year Yankee bonds.
</P>
<P>
With the economy still reeling from the Asian economic crisis,
analysts said the National Government will have to take the lead
in fueling economic growth through heavy deficit spending. The
government expects to overspend and run up a 68-billion-peso (1.7
billion dollars) budget deficit in 1999, they said.
</P>
<P>
National Treasurer Leonor Briones has said the government will
avoid heavy domestic borrowing to avoid putting pressure on
interest rates. 
</P>
