<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Reform of EU Common Agricultural Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'
Alema on Wednesday urged a strong reform of the European Union (EU)
's Common Agricultural Policy (CAP), saying that maintaining the
current status quo of CAP for Italy would be "unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
In a letter to German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who is now
holding the EU rotating presidency, made public as EU agriculture
ministers prepared to resume their work on CAP reform in Brussels,
D'Alema warned against negotiations aimed at consolidating the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
If there are attempts along these lines, he said, Italy will
find the German compromise package "totally unacceptable" and will
not agree to an EU budget which would finance a "CAP which is
still the cause of distortion of competition and products, regions
and farming enterprises."
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said priority in these negotiations must be "a re-
balance of agricultural spending towards products which are not
favored and a re-defining criteria for the use of structural funds
to foster regional prosperity and employment".
</P>
<P>
The work opened by the agricultural ministers, who ended four
days and four night of marathon talks in Brussels last Friday,
must be continued with determination, he added.
</P>
<P>
Also on last Friday, the EU leaders ended informal talks in
Petersberg of Germany, deeply divided on the Agenda 2000 package
of reforms to apply to the EU budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
