<HEADLINE> Brazil's Coffee Production Predicted to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's coffee production
for the 1999-2000 harvest is expected to plunge 25 percent from
the previous harvest to 26.6 million bags (60 kilograms per bag),
said the Association of Coffee Exporters of Brazil (ACEB).
</P>
<P>
The output of the highest quality Arabic style coffee, mainly
for export, will drop by 26.5 percent and robust coffee, most
popular with the industry, may register a fall of 14 percent, the
ACEB predicted.
</P>
<P>
The ACEB also attributed the drastic fall to the bi-annual
cycle of the coffee harvest and estimated the available coffee
reserves at 2 million bags at the beginning of this harvest.
</P>
<P>
ACEB figures showed the country's coffee bean production during
the last harvest was 35.35 million bags, the highest in the past
10 years.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the largest coffee producer in the world. Analysts
said 30 to 32 million bags would be needed for both export and
domestic consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
