<HEADLINE> Brazil's New Central Bank President Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Senate Wednesday
approved Arminio Fraga as the country's Cental Bank president.
</P>
<P>
After three hours of debate, 57 senators voted in favor and 20
against the appointment of the 41-year-old Fraga as the new
president of the Central Bank. Fraga, has been an associate of
billionaire financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the nomination of Fraga was no surprise and was
awaited as much by the government as by the markets.
</P>
<P>
The new president of the Central Bank, who will take the
position officially on Thursday, is considered as a "liberal and
modern" economist.
</P>
<P>
Many Brazilians are frustrated at the apparent lack of progress
at fixing the country's battered economy. Talks with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on an agreement for a 41.5
billion U.S. dollar loan package have dragged on longer than
expected.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is awaiting the next installment of the aid package
arranged by IMF. An announcement on a 9 billion-dollar credit is
expected Friday, which will help boost Brazil's 35.6 billion
dollars in hard currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
Before Fraga's appointment, Brazil's currency rallied late
Wednesday. Traders said the Central Bank moved to prop it up.
</P>
<P>
The real closed at 2.14 to the dollar, after slipping to 2.20
earlier in the day. It had closed Tuesday at 2.17.
</P>
<P>
Since the government stopped its policy of supporting the real
in January, the currency has lost 45 percent of its value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
