<HEADLINE> Venezuela's State Oil Company to Cut Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 12,000 employees of the state-
owned oil company Venezuelan Petroleum (VP) will be made redundant
in the next six months, in line with a strict program of cost
reduction, local reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the company were quoted as saying that employees
would be cut from the present 42,000 to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
The reduction is believed to affect other operations of the
Venezuelan oil industry, including exploration, production,
refining and sales.
</P>
<P>
The company said the reduction measure was a direct consequence
of the prolonged decline of oil prices which began in November
1997 and continues without signs of picking up.
</P>
<P>
The average price of oil exports from Venezuela stood at 10.76
U.S. dollars per barrel in 1998, dropping 5.56 dollars compared to
the 16.32 dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela is the second largest oil producer in the Western
Hemisphere, following Mexico, with more than 2.8 million barrels
produced per day. About 75 percent of the country's oil is
exported.
</P>
<P>
Due to the decline of oil prices, Venezuela's foreign exchange
earnings decreased by more than 7 billion dollars last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
