<HEADLINE> China Launches War against Smuggled Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's ongoing campaign against
smuggled films is crucial if the country is to establish a healthy
domestic film market, says a senior official from the Ministry of
Culture.
</P>
<P>
Today's "China Daily" quotes Liu Yuzhu as saying that the
campaign is also important for the protection of foreign film
exporters' legitimate interests.
</P>
<P>
Strict measures will be taken to crack down on film smuggling,
said Liu. Films shown in Chinese mainland cinemas, which were
neither imported by the China Film Co. (CFC) nor passed
examinations of the Administration of Films under the State
Administration of Radio, Films and Television (SARFT), are
considered to have been smuggled.
</P>
<P>
Ministry and SARFT officials asked governments at all levels,
in an announcement last year, to do everything possible to
eliminate film smuggling, which has had a negative impact on China'
s movie market.
</P>
<P>
The anti-smuggling campaign is a comprehensive program which
requires support from judicial departments, customs and business
circles, Liu stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mao Yu, an official with the administration of films, agrees
with Liu in saying that China's film industry cannot develop
normally unless the smuggling blockbusters is stopped.
</P>
<P>
Smuggled films first appeared in China in the early 1990's, but
have become a nuisance on the mainland in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
China's general box office income was less than 1.5 billion
yuan (180 million US dollars) last year, a drop of 500 million
yuan (60 million US dollars) compared with the highest annual
income recorded earlier this decade, SARFT official announced.
</P>
<P>
China must both produce and import higher-quality films to
satisfy customers' demands, Mao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
