<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Starts Inspection on Italy's Economic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A team of five inspectors from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) began a round of talks Wednesday
to shed some light on the reasons for Italy's poor economic growth
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team, which will be in Italy until March 16, will meet
ministers, employers, unions, financial institutions and other
experts with a list of 12 questions regarding the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the IMF would like to know to what degree Italy'
s poor growth rate can be attributed to macro-economic factors
such as the crises in Asia and in Russia and to what degree it is
a result of "structural" flaws.
</P>
<P>
In December, the IMF revised its 1998 growth forecast for Italy
from 2.1 percent to 1.3 percent and the 1999 forecast from 2.5
percent to 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, who is still
expressing confidence over Italy's potential performance for 1999,
has admitted that the growth rate may be closer to 2 percent than
to the planned 2.5 percent, while the Italian Statistics Bureau
recently announced growth for 1998 at 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The team will also seek to find out why the reduction in
interest rates last year failed to translate into a boost for the
economy.
</P>
<P>
They will also gather opinions on the effects of the end of
government incentives to the auto industry and the minimal impact
of falling world fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
On the structural side, the inspectors, led by Jacques Artus, a
Frenchman, are expected to focus on the privatization process,
which is underway, the possible impact of slower growth, and an
aging population on the pension system.
</P>
<P>
The team is also scheduled to go to Naples to look into
government plans to boost the southern economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Indonesians Say They do Not Feel Safe: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Most people in Indonesia say they
do not feel safe because of the recent bloody riots rocking
various parts of the archipelago, according to a new survey
published by the Jakarta Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted in mid-February, asked a total of 1,234
people in Jakarta, Yogyakarta, Surabaya, Denpasar, Medan and
Ujungpandang about the current standard of public security.
</P>
<P>
Forty-nine percent rated it "bad" while 28 percent said it was
"very bad".
</P>
<P>
When asked where they feel the safest, 79.2 percent said "at
home with the family", 15.4 percent gave "abroad" as their answer,
and 10 percent said "out of towns/villages".
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the poll was conducted by the Resource
Productivity Center for the Jakarta Post and the D and R news
magazine. More than two-thirds of the 1,234 respondents were male,
and more than 80 percent of them are in the 20-44 age group.
Different backgrounds and income levels were represented.
</P>
<P>
When asked to name the most serious threats to their lives,
61.4 percent said riots with religious overtones, 52.5 percent
said widespread crime and 49.6 percent cited ethnic conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been hit by a spate of violence since former
president Soeharto's resignation. Soeharto was forced down on May
21 last year amid the country's worst economic and political
crisis in decades.
</P>
<P>
Most respondents were pessimistic that security would return to
anywhere near normal until after the June 7 general election.
</P>
<P>
When asked about what it would take to restore their sense of
security, 48 percent of those surveyed said the establishment of a
legitimate government after the election, and 37.9 percent
believed that this would not be possible as long as the economic
crisis continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
