<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic Reform Helps Tibetan Serfs Shake Off Fetters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Four decades ago, as evening fell
over Palha Manor in Gyangze County in Tibet, Mima Toizhub, a 19-
year-old serf, prayed for his freedom in a shabby room and wished
he could lead a proper life.
</P>
<P>
Mima Toizhub's prayer came true on March 18, 1959 when the
Chinese Central Government decided to carry out democratic reform
in Tibet to abolish the serfdom system which had been practiced
for more than 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Like his fellow serfs, Toizhub was assigned 21 mu (15 mu is
equal to one hectare) of land and two cows after the democratic
reform.
</P>
<P>
Raidi, a leading official of the Tibet Autonomous Region, said,
"the democratic reform smashed the yoke on the Tibetans." Raidi,
now chairman of the Standing Committee of the Tibet Regional
People's Congress, was also one of millions of serfs in old Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In Tibet's feudal serfdom society, the serfs were the private
property of aristocrats, lamaseries and manors. The law prescribed
that serfs and women were not permitted to be involved in
political and military affairs.
</P>
<P>
Since 1959, the unequal system imposed on the overwhelming
majority of Tibetans has been removed and they are enjoying their
basic rights in various fields.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 7,000 deputies to the people's congress at
county and regional levels which are made up of workers, farmers,
herdsmen, teachers, private businessmen, government officials and
lamas.
</P>
<P>
Of the deputies, Tibetans and the people from other ethnic
groups account for 80 percent and women deputies take up 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
Gyain Tsong, a 67-year-old woman, has been elected as deputy to
the People's Congress in Nedong County for nine terms. Over the
past 30-odd years, she could never forget March 2, 1963 when the
First Session of Nedong County People's Congress was held.
</P>
<P>
Nedong County was the first one in the Tibet Autonomous Region
to set up a people's congress. Gyain Tsong recalled that on the
day the congress opened, people wore new clothes and went on the
streets to take part in singing and dancing parties, adding, "the
celebrations lasted for three days."
</P>
<P>
Daga, a 65-year-old fisherman at Zhuinba Village on the Lhasa
River, said that since 1959, he and his Tibetan villagers have
enjoyed the right to fish.
</P>
<P>
He said that in old Tibet, fishermen, blacksmith and butchers
were looked down upon as "the untouchables".
</P>
<P>
The annual income of Daga's family is now more than 10,000 yuan
and ranked about average in his village. He said, "Now nobody
despises us, and we can freely choose our jobs and enjoy the
fruits of our labor thanks to the motherland."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends Dole to Kosovo for Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States, in an effort
to push diplomatic solution to Kosovo, is sending former Senator
Bob Dole to the Serbian province, U.S. officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said Dole will go to
Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, on Thursday to meet with a
variety of Kosovar Albanian leaders, hoping to win their decision
to sign a peace accord that grants the province complete self-rule,
but short of independence.
</P>
<P>
Other administration officials said veteran diplomat Richard
Holbrooke, the chief architect of the Kosovo cease-fire reached
last October, may make a return visit to Belgrade for talks with
the Yugoslav leaders in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, now nominated for U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, has a long track record in dealing with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, dating from the Dayton peace talks
on Bosnia over three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is eager for a settlement to be
reached before the time peace talks resume in Paris on March 15.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Washington was encouraged by signs that the Kosovar
Albanians had been moving toward accepting the peace deal. Once
the ethic Albanians formally agree, Foley said, "pressure on the
Serbs to do so will mount." 
</P>
