<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Education Aid Benefits Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 6,600 teachers from throughout
China have worked in the Tibet Autonomous Region as part of a
central government education development program initiated in the
mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
An additional 1,400 middle school teachers trained at normal
schools in interior provinces have worked in different parts of
the region since 1976.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 teachers holding either graduate or postgraduate
degrees have voluntarily accepted teaching positions in the region
each year since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six provinces and municipalities have either funded or
offered courses in schools throughout the region. Over 15,000
Tibetan students have attended institutions outside the region and
pursued majors in various courses of study, including finance,
engineering and education. Some 6,000 Tibetan students completed
their studies and returned to the region by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Second National Work Conference on Aid for Tibet in 1987
ended with a State Council decision to allocate six million yuan (
720,000 US dollars) to nine education projects in the region.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the State Council and the former State Education
Commission (now Ministry of Education) jointly sponsored a
conference to discuss education in Tibet. The conference ended
with a decision to allocate 41 million yuan to promote education
in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
