<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sets up Team to Make Asiad Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Sports
Council (KONI) plans to establish a small team next week to
prepare Jakarta's proposal to host the 2006 Asian Games, the
Jakarta Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The team will only prepare arrangement of a proposal for our
bidding offer. We'll submit it to the Olympic Committee of Asia.
After that, KONI will set up another team to conduct further steps,
" KONI outgoing vice chairman Arie Sudewo said.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic Committee of Asia has yet to announce the bidding
deadline. In its constitution and rules chapter 38, it is
designated to open the bidding six years before the Games.
</P>
<P>
Despite controversy surrounding the planned bid for the
quadrennial event at a time of debilitating crisis, Arie was
optimistic long-term preparation could make Indonesia a good host.
</P>
<P>
"This event won't take place next month. We still have seven
years to prepare ourselves. By 2002, hopefully Indonesia will
overcome the economic turmoil", he said.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie has thrown his weight behind KONI's idea,
despite criticism from several sports organizations that it was
unrealistic due to the country's crisis of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Bidding for the Asiad is part of KONI's ambitious Golden Garuda
project, aimed at making Indonesia the host and earning a minimal
sixth-place medal tally finish.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia last hosted the quadrennial event in 1962 in which it
finished in second place behind Japan.
</P>
<P>
Twenty eight years later, during Beijing 1990, Indonesia
launched a bid for the 1998 Asian Games, but was edged out by
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is braced for tight competition against the United
Arab Emirates, India and neighboring Malaysia, all three
reportedly having applied their bidding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
