<HEADLINE> Brembilla Delights Home Crowd with 400 Meter Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Emiliano Brembilla scored a
victory in the men's 400 meters freestyle event in the final
meeting of the short-course swimming World Cup series in Imperia,
Italy, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brembilla, reigning European short-course champion, clocked
three minutes 45.08 seconds to edge out American Chad Carvin, who
was second in 3:45.65. Brazilian Luis Lima finished a distant
third in 3:49.98.
</P>
<P>
Domenico Fioravanti had given Italian fans early cause for
celebration by winning the men's 50m breaststroke in 28.05 seconds
from Sweden's Patrik Isaksson, winner of the 100m breaststroke and
runner-up in the 50m at last December's European short-course
championships in Sheffield, England.
</P>
<P>
Reigning European short-course champion Marcel Wouda of the
Netherlands won the 400m individual medley from German Christian
Keller, who in turn triumphed in the 100m individual medley.
</P>
<P>
World long-course champion Denis Sylantyev of Ukraine won the
200m butterfly in 1:54.94 from Russians Anatoly Poliakov and
Alexander Gorguraki in a repeat of the order in the preceding
World Cup meet in Gelsenkirchen, Germany, last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Agnes Kovacs, 200m breaststroke world long-course champion,
achieved a commanding victory in the 100m breaststroke, having won
all three breaststroke events in Gelsenkirchen in a rare foray
into the short-course scene last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Fellow Hungarians Eva Risztov and Annamaria Kiss also scored
clearcut wins in the 800m freestyle and 200m backstroke
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
