<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Static Electricity First Station for Detecting Static Electricity Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China has built up its first
static electricity station in Shijiazhuang City of northern China'
s Hebei Province in which all static electricity discharge-related
products and materials can be detected.
</P>
<P>
The state-level metrological station is equipped with five
world advanced devices for static electricity detection developed
by a Chinese military scientist.
</P>
<P>
It also introduced advanced devices from the U.S., Britain,
Japan, the Netherlands and some other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Scientists here believe it is of great importance in the fields
of space travel, aviation, petro-chemicals and electronics, as
well as for ammunition storehouses and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Static electricity can cause fires and explosions in filling
stations, ammunition storehouses, or other petroleum or military
installations.
</P>
<P>
Such electric discharges are worldwide headaches in the storage,
usage and development of modern information facilities and
weaponry.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhonghe, a professor at the Mechanical Engineering
Institute of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, said in an
interview with the Science and Technology Daily that his station
was making tests for a kind of U.S.-made static electricity
prevention coating material that is about to be available on the
Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Liu has led the development of world advanced devices in the
electrostatic induction level of electrostatic energy.
</P>
<P>
He also discovered a basic rule for conducting electricity in
high-pressure electrostatic mediums and suggested how to separate
places by grades of electrostatic-fire risk.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
