<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defends Attack on Iraqi Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
defended its bombing of Iraq's pipeline, saying it did not
"intentionally target" oil-related facilities in its attacks on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We can state certainly that we don't intentionally target
infrastructure associated with the oil-for-food program, but this
matter is being looked into," State Department spokesman James
Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to criticisms from Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel, who earlier said Ankara could not accept U.S. strikes in
northern Iraq that led to the closure of a pipeline carrying crude
from Iraq to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.S. warplanes dropped 30 laser-guided bombs on communications
sites, radio relay sites and anti-aircraft guns in northern Iraq
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad said a communications center used to monitor crude
flows through the pipeline had been destroyed in the attack. Iraq
was working around the clock to repair the facilities.
</P>
<P>
Turkey said it has lost some 30 billion dollars in trade with
Iraq due to the imposition of sanctions on its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Foley said U.S. aircraft patroling over Iraq on Feb. 28 and
March 1 hit targets "that were associated with Iraqi attempts to
engage our aircraft."
</P>
<P>
"We are targeting not only air defense radar and weapon
systems, but also other parts of the Iraqi air defense command and
control, early warning, and communications network," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We targeted these facilities because we believe that they
serve a function in the operation of Iraq's air defense system in
that part of the country," he said. "As I said, we're conducting
further analysis of those strikes, and we're cooperating with the
Turkish government in the investigation of this matter." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
