<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Supports Breast-Feeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Breast-feeding has declined
worldwide with devastating consequences for infant and mother
health, women organizations in many countries have alerted.
</P>
<P>
The organizations, with the support of the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF), will launch a joint project to produce a
popular global fact sheet on the economic value of human milk and
of the work of breast-feeding for worldwide distribution.
</P>
<P>
The project aims at uncovering the social contribution of women
in time, energy and money by doing this work, and at informing the
public of the long-term results of breast-feeding, such as savings
in health-care and protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
Breast-feeding is vital to the health and well-being of infants
and young children, yet the work of breast-feeding is not
recognized as an economic contribution.
</P>
<P>
According to fact findings, infants-fed-formula have times the
risk of incurring bacterial infections, four times the risk of
meningitis, and three to four times the risk of middle ear
infections and gastric ailments.
</P>
<P>
Women who do not breast-feed have a higher risk of breast and
ovarian cancers, it was found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
