<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. FAA Orders More 737 Fuel Tank Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) Wednesday ordered Boeing 737 operators to
conduct new inspections of the plane's center fuel tank for
potential wiring problems that could spark a fire inside the fuel
tank.
</P>
<P>
The FAA issued an airworthiness directive, requiring operators
of Boeing 737-100, -200, -300, -400 and -500 series aircraft to
inspect the wiring of the direct current powered float switch, a
device which automatically closes the fueling valve when the fuel
tank is nearly full. That prevents overfilling.
</P>
<P>
The agency order, effective on March 18, requires the removal
and inspection, or deactivation, of the float switch before an
aircraft accumulates 30,000 total flight hours or within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Operators must remove the float switch from the center fuel
tank and inspect the wiring for evidence of chafing, such as
electrical arcing or worn insulation.
</P>
<P>
Depending on the findings, operators may reuse the float switch
and install protective Teflon sleeving and wiring, or install a
new float switch with Teflon sleeved wiring.
</P>
<P>
The cost for deactivation of the float switch and installation
of a caution sign is estimated at 180 U.S. dollars per aircraft,
212,580 dollars for the domestic fleet. The cost for inspection,
removal and reinstallation or replacement of the float switch is
estimated at 1,080 dollars per aircraft, 1.3 million dollars for
the U.S. fleet.
</P>
<P>
The twin-engine Boeing 737 is the most common passenger
aircraft in the world. There are 2,984 planes in the worldwide
fleet that fall within the scope of the airworthiness directive,
of which 1,181 are registered in the United States. Most major
American airlines fly the plane.
</P>
<P>
While the order doesn't apply to foreign carriers, their home
civil aviation authorities tend to follow FAA guidance on safety
matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. Attacks Degrade Iraq' Air Defense System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States has been
substantially degrading Iraq's air defense system by U.S. and
British warplanes's more than 50 attacks since last December's
bombing raids, President Bill Clinton said Wednesday in a report
to Congress.
</P>
<P>
"On over 50 occasions since December, U.S. and coalition forces
have engaged the Iraqi integrated air defense system," Clinton
told Congress. "As a consequence, the Iraqi air defense system has
been degraded substantially further since December."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's report was the latest in a periodic updating of U.S.
action in Iraq. In December, the president sent Congress a letter
about the December 16-19 "Desert Fox" air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the December bombing, Baghdad has denounced no-fly
zones over northern and southern Iraq, claiming that it would be
seen as violation of its air space for Western warplanes to invade
the area, and would be challenged with Iraqi fires.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that since Dec. 23, "we have seen a significant
increase in the frequency, intensity and coordination of the Iraqi
air defense system to counter enforcement of the no-fly zones."
</P>
<P>
The two no-fly zones have been forcefully imposed by the United
States and Britain since the Gulf War in 1991. Washington has been
conducting patrols there to keep Iraq in containment.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States would deepen its ties with
Iraq's opposition groups in an effort to overthrow Saddam
Hussein's regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
