<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Congressional Democrats Proclaim Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
stood Wednesday with Democratic lawmakers who stood with him
during his impeachment trial and said "we are organized and we are
united" as the Republican-controlled Congress gets down to
business.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Democratic leaders pledged
support for a "Families First" agenda of protecting Social
Security and Medicare, improving education and health care and
raising the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
But as much as trumpeting their proposals -- most of which
Clinton highlighted in his State of the Union address in January
-- party officials sought to project an image of unity at a time
when Republicans are still struggling to formulate detailed
legislative plans of their own.
</P>
<P>
The event was the first of its kind since Clinton's impeachment
and trial and coincidentally came on the day that former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky's televised interview was airing on
the American Broadcasting Cooperation (ABC).
</P>
<P>
On February 12, the U.S. Senate ended the impeachment trial
against Clinton and declared acquittal of the president. Clinton,
who went on trial in the Senate on January 7, was charged with
perjury and obstruction of justice in two articles of impeachment
in connection with his relationship with Lewinsky. The two
articles were approved by the House along partisan lines on
December 19 last year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was greeted warmly by House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt, Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle and others who
recently had been sharply condemning his behavior with Lewinsky
and seeking his formal censure rather than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
And onetime rivals Gore and Gephardt embraced in a public
display of unity -- the vice president running for president in
2000, and the other forsaking a White House campaign in hopes of
leading Democrats back into the majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called for a "new energy" in Congress this year and
urged Democrats to look beyond what seems at times "to be
excessive partisanship." 
</P>
</TEXT>
