<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Takes Further Step on Sanctions in Banana Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government ordered
Wednesday importers of selected goods of the European Union (EU)
to post bonds to cover 100 percent duties that may be imposed due
to a trade dispute with Europe over bananas.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Trade Representative Office said the U.S. customs
service beginning Wednesday would require importers of EU goods
ranging from Scottish cashmere sweaters to Italian cheese to post
bonds to cover the threatened duties.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. action followed an announcement Tuesday by arbitrators
of the World Trade Organization (WTO), who had been due to set a
figure for the value of the sanctions, that they needed more
information, and effectively more time.
</P>
<P>
"We had hoped that the arbitrators would complete their work
within the 30 day time schedule called for by WTO rules," U.S.
special trade negotiator Peter Scher said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Today we are taking steps to protect our interests while the
arbitrators complete their deliberations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Scher told a news conference the arbitrators needed the
additional information from the United States and the EU by March
15 and that they hoped for a decision shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
The row centers on the EU's banana regime -- a complicated
system of quotas and marketing arrangements that the EU says is
designed to protect small producer countries mainly in the
Caribbean whose economies are dependent on the fruit.
</P>
<P>
The United States says it actually favors EU-based marketing
companies and is robbing its own big firms of around 520 million
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton Administration has drawn up a list of EU goods
worth 520 million dollars which would be hit by the tariffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Enhancement of African Peacekeeping Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said Wednesday that further progress in the enchancement of
African peacekeeping capacity would only be possible with the
determination of the African states themselves.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, issued here Wednesday,
Annan said, "However, non-African member states will continue to
play a crucial role in the process."
</P>
<P>
"In this context, I welcome the international community's
renewed focus on Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The intensive discussions that have taken place over the past
two years have contributed to a greater political awareness of
needs, brought clarification of a number of vital principles, and
established a conceptual framework for action to build African
peacekeeping capacity," he said.
</P>
<P>
"At present, 22 African countries are contributing almost 2,500
troops to United Nations peacekeeping operations," he said. "I am
grateful for their efforts, which show clearly that enhancement of
African peacekeeping capacity can help advance the cause of peace,
not only in Africa, but around the world."
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan suggested a number of additional steps to
enhance African peacekeeping capacity.
</P>
<P>
These include: the formation of a working group on training,
scholarships and funds that would allow African military officers
to participate in short-term exchanges with U.N. peacekeeping
staff, deployment of U.N. liaison officers to regional
organizations, and the establishment of a special peacekeeping
program for African police officers.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations' experience in resolving African conflicts
attests to the significant role which could be played in Africa
through peacekeeping," Annan said in the report.
</P>
<P>
"The recent setbacks that we have experienced in peacekeeping
efforts in Africa and the recent emergency of new threats to
stability within the continent should not be seen as grounds for
discouragement or disengagement," he said, referring to the
Security Council's recent decision to close down the U.N.
peacekeeping operations in Angola.
</P>
<P>
"Rather, they should be viewed as a call for renewed
cooperation by all state members of the United Nations in favor of
Africa's search for peace, development and democracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A combination of determination, perseverance and vision on the
part of African leaders and commitment by the international
community to support their efforts is vital for peaceful progress
within Africa as well as for enhancing Africa's contribution to
the maintenance of international peace and security," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes Election Outcome in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said here
Wednesday that the presidential elections in Nigeria represent a
significant step on the way to the installation of a
democratically elected civilian government.
</P>
<P>
This occurred after 15 years of military rule, which will be
ended by the handover of power to President-elect Olusegun
Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
In a presidency declaration, the EU said it welcomes the fact
the voting procedures were held on democratic principles, and
congratulates the people of Nigeria on an election held in the
spirit of openness.
</P>
<P>
The EU "appeals to all parties concerned to accept and honor
the results that generally reflect the wish of the Nigerian
people."
</P>
<P>
"The European Union is aware that the newly elected president
and his government have a major task before them" and "assures the
Nigerian people and government of its willingness to continue to
promote political and economic reforms and its readiness to
cooperate with the elected authorities towards strengthening the
rule of law," the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European bloc in its declaration hopes that "the
new government, in the interest of the entire country, will be
able to succeed in reconciling all those who opposed each other in
the past and will thus lead Nigeria to a better future and enable
it to assume its due role in the international community of states
and peoples." 
</P>
</TEXT>
