<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges U.N. to Stop U.S. Aggression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Wednesday called on
the United Nations Security Council to carry out its
responsibilities and stop the U.S. aggression against it.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Security Council, Iraqi Minister for Foreign
Affairs Mohammed Said Al-Sahaf said the American aggression on
February 28 and March 1 caused serious damage to the Iraqi oil
facilities in the northern part of the country and led to the full
cessation of pumping operation of crude oil through the
Iraqi/Turkey pipeline.
</P>
<P>
"This meant a daily loss of financial resources under the
Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) of 1 million barrel a day, which
equals 9 million U.S. dollars a day, in addition to the
humanitarian and material serious damage," Sahaf said.
</P>
<P>
"This aggression by the American planes which attacked the
Iraqi oil operation system in addition to the practices of the
representatives of the Untied States in the 661 Committee aiming
at hindering the contracts of oil sector under the MOU stands as a
clear evidence to the American decision to destroy Iraqi
capabilities of exporting oil, in order to achieve the suspicious
objectives of the American Administration that go beyond these
strikes and try to stop the implementation of the MOU signed
between Iraq and the United Nations," Sahaf said.
</P>
<P>
Sahaf said this aggression was also part of the American
practices against Iraq in order to destabilize its security and
stability by interfering in its internal affair.
</P>
<P>
Sahaf urged the Security Council to carry out its
responsibilities under the U.N. Charter to maintain international
peace and security and stop this aggression against Iraq which
represents a serious threat to peace and security in the region
and in the whole world.
</P>
<P>
U.S. airstrikes on February 28 damaged Iraq's Kirkuk pipeline
in the northern part of the country. This pipeline carries half
the oil Iraq is permitted to export under the terms of the
Security Council resolutions establishing the oil-for-food
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
