<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Artificial Skin" Brings New Hope for Injured Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- British veterinarians have
successfully carried out animal surgeries using a new
"artificially growing skin" that helps deep wounds to heal.
</P>
<P>
The material is made from pig intestine, a by-product of the
food industry which is purified to make a collagen membrane, BBC
One's Tomorrow's World reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The collagen membrane acts as a framework or scaffold that
provides a structure above which new tissue can grow, the TV
program said.
</P>
<P>
When it is sewn into a wound, growth proteins contained in the
membrane encourage cells and blood vessels to grow. As the wound
heals, the collagen dissolves away to leave an even layer of new
skin.
</P>
<P>
The new treatment has so far been tried in a cat and a dog with
encouraging results, and it was reported that the new material
will shortly be available on the UK market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves to Increase Petrol, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament Wednesday
approved tax increases for all forms of energy from April as part
of the government's so-called environmental tax reform.
</P>
<P>
Petrol tax will rise by 0.04 dollars to a total of 0.61 dollars
per liter, meaning that motorists will have to pay a minimum of
0.88 dollars at the pumps.
</P>
<P>
Electricity tax is to rise by 0.01 dollars per kilowatt-hour,
heating oil tax will increase to 0.07 dollars per liter, up from
0.02 dollars, and natural gas tax will jump to 0.40 dollars from
the current 0.19 dollars per kilowatt-hour.
</P>
<P>
The tax increase, which is aimed at reducing energy use, will
yield 4.94 billion dollars to the government during the coming
year after its April 1 introduction. In 2000 it will cost
consumers 7.29 billion dollars in extra taxes.
</P>
<P>
Funding will be used to reduce contributions to state pensions
to 19.5 percent from 20.3 percent of gross wage or salary.
</P>
<P>
The energy tax rise vote in the Bundestag, the parliament's
lower chamber, was 332 for and 299 against. Approval for the bill
is not required from the upper house, the Bundesrat.
</P>
<P>
Opposition conservatives attacked the tax increase. "This will
have severe consequences for the German economy and divert
investment and jobs abroad," said Hans Michelbach, a member of the
Christian Democratic alliance (CDU/CSU).
</P>
<P>
Michelbach said German businesses and consumers were already
suffering under energy taxes that were 15 to 25 percent higher
than in other European Union countries and up to 30 percent higher
than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
This was rejected by the government which pointed out it had
arranged special exemptions for industry, farmers and the public
transport sector, which reduced the energy tax increase burden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990304.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
