<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Warns of Smoking Impact on Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO) said Wednesday that tobacco may kill up to 10
million people by 2020 from killing 4 million today if the control
measures are not taken.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries may account for 70 percent of the tobacco
deaths as tobacco multinations are shifting their focus to these
countries, the WHO said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
According to the WHO's Tobacco Free Initiative study, smoking
already accounts for 75,000 deaths a year in China. The figure
will rise to 3 million by the time today's young smokers reach
middle age.
</P>
<P>
The WHO has started exploratory talks with international donor
agencies to assist farmers during the period of transition from
tobacco to other crops.
</P>
<P>
The WHO believes that the world's current 1.2 billion smokers
could crop to between 800 million to 1 billion in the medium term
under good control measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
