<HEADLINE> Schroeder Not to Change Planned Tax Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
told German insurance executives Wednesday he would not change
planned tax reforms but held out the prospect of some form of
relief if industry predictions on total costs of closing tax
loopholes turned to be true.
</P>
<P>
Both sides had agreed to examine the actual costs imposed by
the tax reform at the end of the year, government spokeswoman
Charima Reinhardt said on the same day.
</P>
<P>
"There is a promise we can examine the case again should it
turn out -- and we don't believe it will -- that the insurance
sector's estimate was more precise than the government's," a
Finance Ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
There is a gulf between what the Finance Ministry says the tax
reform will cost insurance companies and what the companies
themselves say they will wind up paying.
</P>
<P>
The additional tax will total 5.2 billion dollars, while the
insurance sector predicts it will pay 8.24 billion dollars,
according to the German government.
</P>
<P>
Germany's biggest insurance company, Allianz, has threatened to
move its headquarters, or at least some of its operations, from
Germany due to the tax increase. 
</P>
