<HEADLINE> Cohen to Discuss Iraq, Peace Process with Mideast Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen
will discuss issues concerning U.S. security interests, including
Iraq and the Middle East peace process with leaders of Middle East
nations during his visit there, a senior U.S. defense official
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a briefing ahead of Cohen's eight-day visit starting on
Friday, the senior official added that the defense secretary would
also discuss ways to solidify bilateral military ties with them.
</P>
<P>
He will go to Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, Oman, the United Arab
Emirates, Qatar and Kuwait in the Gulf and complete the trip with
high-level meetings in Jordan, Egypt and Israel before returning
home on March 12.
</P>
<P>
"We will obviously talks about Iraq. We have gotten very, very
good support from all our friends in the Gulf. We will continue to
discuss overall strategies on how to deal with Saddam Hussein,"
the official said, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's bombing raids against Iraq, the United
States and Britain have launched a series of attacks on Iraqi air
defense sites in both northern and southern no-fly zones they have
imposed since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has ever since the December bombing proclaimed it would
no longer recognize the no-fly zones and would challenge any
Western warplanes invading its airspace.
</P>
<P>
The senior official said Saudi Arabia and Kuwait had no
objection for increasing raids against Iraq's air defense system.
"The Gulf countries are quite comfortable with what we are doing,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In Jordan, Egypt and Israel, Cohen will hold talks with their
leaders on bilateral military ties and the deadlocked peace
process there, the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"We will talk about the peace process and emphasize the
importance of having that go forward," he said. 
</P>
