<HEADLINE> Neo-Nazi Crimes Drop, Anti-Semitic Crimes Up in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of reported neo-Nazi and
far-right crimes in Germany dropped slightly last year, but
anti-Semitic crimes rose, according to Interior Ministry figures
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were 7,414 reported right-wing extremist crimes in
Germany during 1998, a drop of almost 5 percent over the previous
year, said the ministry in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Reported violent neo-Nazi crime dropped by 19 percent to 257
cases in 1998 and racist violent crime fell by 6 percent to 434
cases, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Semitic crimes rose by 1.5 percent last year with 991
reported incidents, said the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Violent anti-Semitic crimes in Germany rose by 45 percent to a
total of 16 last year, compared with 11 in 1997 and six cases in
1994, the figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Extremist crimes were up almost 4 percent to 3,201 in 1998, but
violent leftist crime fell by 10 percent to 626 reported cases,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Adding figures for politically motivated crimes by foreigners
there were a total of 16,605 reported extremist crimes in Germany
last year, up 1.2 percent, of which 1,591 were violent crimes,
down almost 12 percent from 1998, said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
