<HEADLINE> Kenya Dominates World Pyrethrin Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya exported 7,000 tons of the
pyrethrin derived from pyrethrum, out of the 13,000 tons required
by the world market in 1998, Director Tom Kibisu of the Pyrethrum
Board of Kenya (PBK) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kibsu said that Kenya exported 80 percent of world's pyrethrin
-- a chemical extracted from dry pyrethrum flowers, according to
a local media.
</P>
<P>
Pyrethrin is used for the manufacture of insecticides and is
preferred to other chemicals because it is environment-friendly.
</P>
<P>
The PBK also said in a report that pyrethrum farmers in Nakuru
District in central Kenya, a leading pyrethrum grower, earned 414
million Shillings (about 6.7 million U.S. Dollars) for the 4,016
tons of the commodity they delivered to the Pyrethrum Board of
Kenya last year.
</P>
<P>
The district, which posted the largest yield nationally,
produced 3,323. 9 tons in 1996/97 and earned 320.4 million
Shillings (some 5.2 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the adverse effects of the El Nino rains in early 1998
which led to a decline in pyrethrum production, the pyrethrin
content remained constant at 1.49 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
