<HEADLINE> Schroeder Urges German Greater Industry Backing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
is to meet with the bosses of leading industrial companies next
week in a bid to get better support by corporations for the Expo
2000 in Hanover, according to sources of the German government
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Economics Minister Werner Mueller said the government remains
worried about what it sees as insufficient corporate support for
the world exposition set for June 1 to October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Additional efforts of German companies are required in order
to secure Germany's showing on the international stage," he said
in a report to the cabinet about the preparations for the
exposition.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the bosses of 34 companies had been
invited to an evening dinner at the Chancellory on March 10, with
so far 29 having promised to attend. Those invited comprise the
"cream of the crop" of Germany's corporations, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The development follows a period of uncertainty in the
preparations for the Expo 2000. Organizers have had to revise
their financial planning amid increasingly sober calculations
about how many visitors the exposition will attract.
</P>
<P>
German industry is supposed to bear a 40 percent share of the
basic capital of the exposition organizing company, Expo GmbH, but
the actual support is still lagging far below that amount,
Chancellory Office sources said.
</P>
<P>
Expo GmbH has so far lined up 17 companies for sponsorship
deals with 450 million marks (253 million U.S. dollars). A further
100 license and concession deals have also been finalized.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest calculations, the federal German government
and the state of Lower Saxony -- where Hanover is the capital --
are to share the burden in covering up to 200 million marks' worth
of losses and in financing reserves of the same amount of money.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Bonn and Hanover have raised the total credit
guarantee volume to 1.77 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
Hanover is expecting 20 to 30 million visitors to the
five-month exposition, which will see a record participation by
187 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
