<HEADLINE> EU Warns Greece Not to Violate Competition Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS March 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission warned
Greece on Wednesday not to violate European Union (EU)'s
competition rules because the EU member state failed to lifted all
restrictions on the operation of mobile telecommunications
services, nor liberalize its satellite services and alternative
networks.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body said in a statement that it has decided
to send five reasoned opinions to Greece since it has found that
Greece has not informed the commission of its operation in the
field of telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU's Liberalization Directives and the
Telecommunications Regulatory Package, the commission said, the
Greece should have taken all necessary measures for the abolition
of special and exclusive rights for the provision of satellite
services.
</P>
<P>
It should also take steps to ensure that any operator is
entitled to provide satellite services in its territory under a
relevant directive, the EU executive said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country had not adopted procedure and conditions
for issuing certain telecommunications licenses, nor legislation
to lift the restrictions on international interconnection systems.
</P>
<P>
A gradual liberalization of the European telecommunications
market has taken place since 1990. As a result, the European
market was fully opened to competition in most EU member states in
January 1, 1998. Greece has been allowed to postpone the market
liberalization until December 31, 2000, but it still failed to
fulfil its obligations under the EU treaty, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Greece government has been given two months from
the receipt of the reasoned opinions to comply with its findings,
otherwise it will be filed in the European Court of Justice, the
European Commission concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
