<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Clears Italian Aid to Fight Illegal Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELES, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's executive
body Wednesday approved an Italian state aid scheme designed to
help bring undeclared workers back into the official labor force.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission said the Italian government proposed
so-called "realignment contracts" to encourage firms in Italy's
southern regions "to realign wages in the underground economy."
</P>
<P>
Through the contracts, employers undertake to bring undeclared
workers into compliance with the law. They also need to take steps
to "gradually increase the level of their wages and social
security contributions to those provided for under national
collective agreements," the commission said.
</P>
<P>
The aid is designed to maintain jobs and the commission said
has authorized it under the guidelines on employment aid.
</P>
<P>
In Italy's relevant regions, the EU executive said, the
situation regarding undeclared labor is particularly serious. The
proportion of illegal workers in the southern regions account for
33.57 percent of the whole labor force.
</P>
<P>
The background to this is an underdeveloped economy in areas,
which are highly dependent on sectors with particularly high level
of undeclared labor, such as the agricultural sector, the
commission added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
